    text: `<p>It is absolutely possible to change the entire life in a couple of years. Even if your souls seems to be lost or at least broken as hell, even if your past is haunting you, and even of you think you’re a gone case. There’s just one little thing really necessary for that, and that thing is called *a desire*. An utmost, true desire to change, to get a new life, or just to get a life.</p>
<p>You’ll never be good in lofty matters if you’re both feet on—or in?—the ground.</p>
<p>For sure, there’s always a safe haven of stiff upper lip, pretending to be completely *fine* all the time, not letting anyone see anything. Deceiving own self, maybe, but well. Still better than let yourself think about what is truth.</p>
Truth is something that Moran seems never to admit. That stubbornness may seem childish a little bit, like he’s a teen with ‘not a passing phase’, yet that’s his own way to go on living. If you pretend too well maybe it becomes true.</p>
<p>That's all fine. At least, for now; and maybe the ghosts of the past still visit almost every night, it’s okay to live with it. Well, he’s just another one vet, and who’s sane after years of war? War is a nice bitch to blaim. Especially when you don’t want to acknowledge anything else.</p>
<p>Well-known things give a nice feeling of normality. Even if the things are quite dirty, but well—someone has to be a bad guy, so why not. Moran never was a kid glove, neither he was a prig. But he was a very qualified professional, and he was called the best sniper of his generation at least here in the UK and maybe Europe, and that’s what he’s simply proud of. No wonder he easily found an employer as soon as he had decided to come back.</p>
<p>Right now, getting ready to make his work done, Moran feels something isn’t right. He can’t say what exactly, but that’s a kind of sixth sense which maybe every expirienced vet has: a feeling of unknown danger. But well, he studied the site well, he knows all the ways to quickly get out, he has a perfect point of view, his gun is in ideal state. What could go wrong, as they say.</p>
<p>And as soon as Moran gets his ‘client’ in sight, he knows that everything goes wrong right now. Because either the dead man can come to life or he had finally lost his marbles. Both is bad, really, really fucking bad.</p>
<p>Time suddenly stands still. His finger lies on the trigger having a perfect momentum for a gentle push that would send the bullet right into the head, making a brilliant, beautiful shot. <p>At this moment, Moran knows that his victim *knows* that. Gives him an opportunity to shoot. Gives him *a choice* he never had.</p>
<p>A slight shining comes through the pocket. Sound is off, as well as vibration, yet Moran knows he has an incoming call right now.
He knows it’s the dead man.</p>
<p>Finger is still on the trigger when Moran reaches carefully for his phone, answering the call but keeping silence. Well, he never was the one to speak first, so why starting now.
Of course it’s absolutely not becase the throat is suddenly dry and like out of air; it’s not like his hands could shake when holding a gun, but something inside can shake. Or maybe it’s the bloody world shaking, who knows.</p>`
};

// PAGE 3 (JM)
pagesData[2] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>It's an early morning and the block seems impossibly quiet. There's an endless silence on the line before a familiar, soft-spoken voice starts murmuring:</p>
<p>"Y'know, I've always been curious about the intimacy you exchange with people at your gunpoint. I can almost feel your crosshairs stroking my neck. Sends shivers down my spine, honestly..."</p>
<p>There's about half a mile separating them but still it's as if JM was whispering right in Moran's ear. He stretches a little, making himself a little bit more comfortable in the spotlight, and all the sighing noises seem pretty alive. But it's only 50/50 true right now...</p>
<p>"Why, one curiosity fulfilled. Now I'm really thrilled to know how you're gonna crack this dilemma. I can 'stay dead and outta this world', and you can get your work done for your new boss. That's what you're all about, ain't you? Getting work done. Or you can... hmm, I dunno." 
<p>Finally he turns around to face the tall window and looks out onto the empty street. Moran can see him and he's the same and also different, but it's hard to say how.</p>
<p>"But before you do anything I gotta tell you that you won't be getting any money for this job. Your new boss, well, he's gooone."</p>
<p>Which means he's a corpse already, certainly.</p>
<p>JM smiles in contentment.</p>
<p>"So, whaddya think?"</p>`
};

pagesData[3] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>Impossible. Absolutely impossible, abso-fucking-lutely impossible. Dead people are dead, they’re not waking up and speaking in a bloody familiar soft voice, intonating skillfully, with that bloody unique accent. Moran is still silent, listening to every word, almost holding his breath, and it seems to him that his perfectly steady heartbeat begins skip a beat every now and then.</p>
<p>Fucking impossible, Moran thinks, his finger frozen on the trigger. It feels like right now nothing would make him pull it.
Getting work done, truly? Words so simple yet too meaningful. How often Moran would say he’s simply getting work done when trying to deceive hell knows whom, maybe himself, that it’s only about the job? Specific one yet just a job.
Maybe it was only him who really wanted to be deceived.</p>
<p>That man talking to him in one-of-a-king voice finally turns his face. That’s when the heart truly skips few beats, and breath stops for a short while until the body cries for some fresh oxygen.
<p>For two fucking years Moran was perfectly sure that he’s dead. He saw the moment, dammit. He couldn’t do anything while being almost mile away, but he could see, and that haunted him all through those two years.
<p>Not that James had some utterly unique features. No, that freak was maybe distinctive enough yet he was not a fucking snowflake — there were people looking like him; there were voices talking in same accent; there were dark eyes staring same intensely. But there was something still making him fucking unique. A combination of all those small not-so-special things, a mix of stare and voice, and manners, and smile, and whatever bullshit.
Right now Moran could swear on blood this is the very JM he once knew. His sharp intuition knows that. His eyes see that. His ears hear. And only poor little voice of reason tries to call, telling dead men tell no tales.</p>
<p>Dead man stares at him as if he knows where exactly Moran is. Or rather, he does know. James, a freaking genius, quickly understood any principles he wanted to understand. So it took him only a few month to perfectly understand all the ballistics to choose a perfect sniper spot considering all the small factors. He did know where Sebastian is every single time, making not a guess but a perfect calculation.</p>
<p>Same he knows now. Smiling so self-confidently, staring right into the cross hairs. Waiting for an answer with a suprising patience. A man who put through a perfect combination.</p>
<p>Moran realizes his lips are completely dry and his finger is off the trigger. He locks his rifle mindlessly while watching through the glass, and when he answers, his voice sounds too low and a tiny bit hoarse.</p>
<p>"Does is actually matter what I think?" Moran chooses his words carefully, as if treading the minefield, but then emotions speak faster than he would want. "You’re dead, you’re fucking dead, what should I think, you bastard?"</p>`
};

pagesData[4] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>Even though the board was set very carefully for this little negotiation, there was still one thing JM wasn't too happy with – and that not being able to actually see Moran in this moment. To see his body positioned on the top of a roof, intertwined with the sniper mount: he always found the look of it very graceful when given the chance to spy on his work through a nearby camera he managed to connect to. It was better than watching a show about tigers on the Discovery Channel. Would make him so damn horny every other day.</p>
<p>Though it's not like horny was the only emotion JM was capable of. It's natural to get some perfomance anxiety while showing up like that. He learnt a thing or two about ballistics thanks to observing Moran and figured he was staring in the right direction, otherwise this would be fucking awkward.</p>
<p>JM regretted he couldn't see Sebastian's forearms tense, his face focused, his legs open and a knee bent. He closed his eyes for a moment and tried to imagine the touch of the crosshairs sliding across his own body, as if deciding whether to shoot, and which part of it to shoot off first. Nervousness nah, but excitement was almost making his knees weak.</p>
<p>However, being one-sidedly exposed like this, JM was still in charge.</p>
<p>"Careful now..." he whispered dangerously at the hint of anger in Moran's voice. Oh there were times when he enjoyed getting on his nerves just for fun, getting him all riled up, testing his limits and his self-control only to relish his excruciating desire to fucking act on it. But for now he needed to force Moran into repeating their dance of undisputed subordination step by step, ending in regiving the oath Sebastian already gave once.</p>
<p>(No matter how badly JM himself wanted to skip this playing hot-n-cold and sink his teeth into Moran's flesh and see that he still belongs to James Moriarty- or that he, once again, chooses to belong to James Moriarty).</p>
<p>It is a minefield, yes.</p>
<p>They can't get as close as they used to be, not right away.</p> 
<p>And it's not like Sebastian got a green light to play hard-to-get for JM to pick up on him with an A-level courtship. First, he has to make a choice, second, he gotta prove himself loyal and worthy. But, before everything else...</p>
<p>"How about we get a coffee? Think about this," he says, after fidgeting his fingers against the window glass thoughtfully.</p>
<p>He's sleepy, but again, it's pretty natural for 5 AM or so.</p>`
};

pagesData[5] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>Right now the rifle is still in Moran's hands. It would take just a couple of seconds to release the safety catch again and pull the trigger. Dead man is still perfectly in the center of aiming cross, so one shot will make the work done. A beautiful, professional-quality death. If not the shattered glass, would be even clean and nice.
That whisper through the phone was sending cold shivers down the spine. Gosh, if only he had a few minutes to think.</p>
<p>Usually Moran doesn't need much time to think. He can act immediately, gracefully changing any plans in case if everything goes wrong: war was a good tutor and gave many painful lessons. Some inner rules were written by blood; so no one could say Moran is a slow-thinker. Moreover, this specific talent of a ready wit was actually something that attracted JM's attention a great while ago.</p>
Speaking of which.</p>
<p>Moran has to make a great effort, summoning up all his will and all the self-control a good sniper could have, and making himself think.</p>
<p>So, either it's true and James is alive (which, in turn, could be also a sign of insanity; but that's the other question), or it's some other freak playing tricks with him. Actually, if trying to think cold, both options lead to one way out.</p>
<p>Fuck the sight. He has to see that not-so-dead man face to face. And then he would decide, or maybe die, or whatever.</p>
<p>All of a sudden, at this moment Moran doesn't even think of own safety which has always been a kind of a big no-no for his brain. Yet now the inner voice is stunned and silent, and dammit.</p>
<p>He can't miss that chance if it's really some kind of crazy, impossible chance.</p>
<p>And actually, Moran still hates coffee. James knows that perfectly.</p>
<p>"A block to the west," he says dryly, "don't you dare playing tricks with me."</p>
Sebastian hangs up because he knows next moment he could lose control of his voice. He doesn't move until JM does; he doesn't pack his rifle until JM walks away from sight. His hands aren't shaking at all.</p>
<p>And actually, maybe this cold outside is just the first stage of the inner storm that will turn him inside out.</p>
<p>Honestly, Moran doesn't need a rifle to kill. He can easily do it with bare hands.
Only approaching the doors of 24/7 coffeeshop he understands that he's been walking too fast. Hands still don't shake, and his fake front is still all composed.</p>`
};

pagesData[6] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>JM accepts the terms immediately and, when the phonecall is dismissed, he leaves the building throughout the emergency exit, feeling delighted to recognize the same old Moran he once knew: disciplined, taciturn, decisive.</p>
<p>It's windy and his hair gets somewhat messy. Apparently they travel parallel streets, and he arrives a little bit late only to find Moran is already there.</p>
<p>JM adjusts his outfit in the reflection of the storefront and enters the coffeeshop, looking almost nonchalant in his shades. He studies the room and it's perfectly empty, except for them two early birds. Too bad, he thinks, because if Moran intents to beat the shit outta him, there would be nothing to stop him from it.</p>
<p>JM has a 0.33 in his pocket. It's not like he's gonna use it but you can't trust anyone these days, really. He orders a simple black coffee and places himself at the small table in the corner, in front of his ex-employee.</p>
<p>The coffee is shitty but at least it'll keep him functional for a few more hours. He takes the shades off and stares at Moran from under the heavy, languid eyelids, waiting for him to speak his mind.</p>
<p>JM wonders if the unhealthy skin tone and deep-set eyes make him look more like a shadow or a ghost of who he used to be, which is not very convincing on the behalf of his alive-ness. Sebastian seems unimpressed and almost hostile, however, there's always been a touch of "I'm so done with your bullshit" to his expression, and JM knows it's only a facade. Oh no, his vanity tells him that nobody can remain unbothered next to James Moriarty, plus he used to know Sebastian too well. His icy shell is trying so hard not to melt under JM's burning fingers, and he'll never make it obvious.</p>
<p>It's such a temptation to see his fake tranquility crumble. But they're civilized people, sitting in a civilized place, talking in a civilized way. Ain't they? They even might appear as two businessmen having an early breakfast, if it weren't for Sebastian's practical, semi-military clothing.</p>
<p>The air feels electric, and JM's not sure if he should sit with his legs criss-crossed or spread because of how this tension resonates between his thighs. There's a smell of urban dust and cigarettes coming from Moran – a familiar smell which is so good...</p>`
};

pagesData[7] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>That bloody coffeeshop is empty, except for a snoozy guy at the counter. There’s absolutely no need for drinks right now yet the habit to ‘look normal’ makes Moran order a cup of black tea. Tea in a coffeeshop, could be actually funny. He won’t drink it anyway, but it’s a small basic rule: once you want to sit down in some boozer, make some order.</p>
<p>From a table in the corner he can see the whole room and a bit of street. Fine enough for paranoia. Also, some distance giving time to make sure he can regain temper as soon as somebody enters.</p>
<p>And goddammit, he really needs that fucking time. The moment another one early visitor enters the coffeeship, stupid heart skips a couple of beats, making it hard to keep calm at least visibly. There can’t be any mistake, there’s just one crazy, unreal fact: Moriarty is alive.
A good observation skill could tell it from any movement, from the way he walks in or keeps his hand in a pocket, or his tone when making order; those fucking shades and the whole look. All the manners.</p>
<p>No fucking way, Moran thinks while keeping himself perfectly quiet. Like it's just a usual business meeting. Like he meets dead men every other day. He stays silent while watching every JM’s move. Somewhere deeps inside it echoes with an old habit almost forgotten, or he thought forgotten. To be a silent observer of a devil in disguise.</p>
The devil stares back, taking his shades off, and that’s the very rapier glance lost for two bloody years. Well, Moran holds these black eyes not giving a tiniest reaction. His long slender fingers locked in front of him on the table are perfectly motionless. It’s something inside that shivers and shakes, and it shall stay inside.</p>
<p>"So you’ve been dead," he finally says, voice a bit hoarse— voice of a man who rarely speaks but often smokes.</p>
<p>For a moment Moran thinks it’s just his mind completely lost, and maybe there’s noone in front of him, maybe just the images that haunt him stepped on a new level, going from nightmares to realistic hallucinations. He’s always been a good observer, yeah, so he could easily recreate any movement, any reaction and any glance in his imagination. A bitter curse, to remember JM so well.</p>
<p>"Why alive all of a sudden now? Why reaching me, or are there hiring troubles down in hell?"</p>
<p>Hand on heart, Moran has absolutely no idea what should he say, or if he should at all. Moreover, neither he knows what he want to hear in response. Something small, backstabbing and poison deep on the bottom of the heart tells that it doesn’t matter what, it only matters who says.</p>
<p>Some reasonable part of Sebastian just wants to grab Moriarty by his throat and beat the shit out of him until he’s dead again. Not that he always listens to his reasonable part though</p>`
};

pagesData[8] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>Sebastian Moran belongs to that tiny group of people, who, in the whole world, can recognize James Moriarty by his movement as a physical being, and not just an urban legend; some abstract, creative force on the global arena. And he's aware.

A good sniper is a good tactician, always choosing a vantage point with the best view of the terrain and his target. Sebastian Moran managed to capture the top of this hill; observe James Moriarty not only from the distance of his telescopic sight, but from the distance of a stretched arm, and closer even. He used to be by his side quite literally, close enough to study the curve of his nose and the length of his lashes. 

In the system of total anonymity this can make him a friend or a foe, depending on how JM feels about it. Surely, this fact adds to the level of possible sentimentality between them, though it's not like JM decided to reach for Moran out of pure sentiment. 


"What happened to Hello?" he exclaims teasingly, as if he was the one to say it very often. "Hi, boss, you look wonderful and not dead in the slightest? ... By the way, how are you so sure I went to Hell and not to Heaven?" 

He doesn't wait for a reply, falling on his habit of taking the lead in conversation. 

"It's so fucking tedious, being dead, y'know. It stinks, everything itches, brrr, I figured I just couldn't take it anymore." 

The tip of his shoe bumped against Moran's boot, because the table was so small, hardly leaving them space to maneuver without some accidental – or intentional – touching. 

Maybe Moran's positioning in the corner is not working for his advantage after all 'cause now he's trapped into the corner by JM. 

"Besides... Our friend, Sherlock, is back. Haven't you heard?" 

While sipping at his coffee, he eyes Moran once again with great attention. Time to get jealous, he thinks, 'cause it's always about Sherlock. It was about Sherlock two years ago when he decided to blow his own brains out just to outplay that smart-ass detective.</p>`
};

pagesData[9] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>It actually feels a little bit creepy, because right at this moment it feels like nothing has changed, like last two years were just another one long nightmare. Moriarty always was a chatterbox, and while for some people it was just annoying, for Moran it was some kind of personal meditation. Simply listening, while never missing a thing, rarely saying something in response. Ironically, it was a weird kind of balance between two of them.</p>

<p>So it was happening right now. JM was talking, his voice full both of vivid and subtle tones, obviously not waiting for any answers. A one-man theatre.</p>
<p>Could be even entertaining if it wasn't about exactly that one man.</p>
<p>Freaking coffeeshop has small tables, and very uncomfy chairs. Or maybe everything seems uncomfy now. Moran realizes he can't move back even a little bit, caught in a self-made trap.</p>
<p>Of course he can easily leave if he wants. Not like Moriarty can be a real rival when it comes to simple physical interaction. The question is, Moran has no idea if he wants to leave.</p>
<p>Yet the next words make him shortly growl under his breath.</p>
<p>Of fucking course. Like there could be any other reason to come back from dead.</p>
<p>"Your friend, you mean? Or shall I say, your wet dream?"</p>
<p>Moran's voice sounds bit hissing now. He leans back in his chair, arms folded across his chest as if taking the defensive position. This doesn't actually change the distance between them. And moreover, it's an absolute fail.</p>
<p>Putting it straight, JM always was capable to detect slightest emotions no matter how Moran masked them, and he was actually not bad in keeping his poker face. So even when Moran did his best to hide everything, he still was in plain sight for Moriarty.</p>
<p>But right now he doesn't even try. Sebastian knows it's a huge mistake, but actually... he doesn't give a fuck anymore. Inside some kind of storm is going to rise, and maybe the facade is still quite restrained, heartbeat loses its rhythm.</p>
<p>Maybe it's just too much.</p>
<p>Above everything else, Moran wants to feel completely nothing. An impossible dream. A will-o'-the-wisp leading him right into the deep slough of mixed feelings, 'cos right now he even can't be sure if he's happy to see Moriarty alive or hates it.</p>
<p>Deep inside, there's a bitter understanding that he actually never can say 'no' to JM. Never could he, and after two fucking years, never would.</p>`
};

pagesData[10] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>The first emotion to slip through the shields of indifference is spiteful, but JM seems unbothered, stretching himself on his seat almost like it's a sunlounger (which is way easier for him considering his size). This first hint of Moran's weakness is actually an appetizer before the feast for JM to thrive on.</p>
<p>To be honest, he was starting to feel his desperation increase already, becoming impatient trying to get through Sebastian's cold demeanor. But now that he managed to get something, he felt more collected. Though deep down he still wanted it to the extreme: Sebastian's hands on him, grabbing and pulling at the lapels of his new Westwood, unleashing the rage of a betrayed man full-force – this would be perfect.</p>
<p>Imperfection can drive Moriarty mad, and there's a lot of things that just don't feel right. The norms of society which force them to sit there like nothing happened instead of furiously fighting or fucking – this doesn't feel right.</p>
<p>The fact that Sherlock outsmarted his checkmate situation by faking his death, and now he's back, and he still hasn't given enough appreciation to Moriarty's genius by choosing him above everyone else, and JM is still not over that Mr Know-it-all, and will probably never be until one of them – or both – are actually dead.</p>
<p>This maddening obsession is what brought JM back, but he doesn't feel guilty about admitting this crushing truth in front of Moran. It's disgusting; JM knows he's disgusting.</p>
<p>"You asked the question. Don't act like you couldn't see this coming," he smiles a fakely apologetic smile, then leans closer. </p>
<p>"The thing is: it seems like you're unemployed right now, and I'm offering you a job, and you'd benefit by accepting my offer. But, despite this being the best outcome for you anyway, you're still free to say no, and this is why I'm gonna grant you exactly one wish to make you feel better. So... What is that you want?" he walks his index and middle fingers across the table towards Sebastian and tickles his hand lightly with the tip of his finger. This little gesture is shy and playful and somewhat girlish at the same time.</p>`
};

pagesData[11] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>For the whole life Moran was taught to keep calm in any situation. Whatever happens, keep your head, never let emotions take over, cage the rage, be armed with patience. Well, a big advantage, if you think of it, and also a necessary skill for a good sniper.
Yet right now he feels like all the years of such experience can vanish in a blink of an eye. Looking straight in dark eyes, as if trying to read something between the lines, Moran feels an unbearable tension in his hands.

And actually, yes, he asked the question and got the answer, and it's so fucking routine when JM is absolutely right with a grain of salt and his well-played fake smile.

It takes effort not to move and keep sight line when Moriarty leans closer. It takes bigger effort to stay visibly calm while listening to that velvet, cushioned voice.
Yet when Moran feels that very slight touch, something inside cracks and breaks.

"What is that I want?" he asks, his voice still calm and cold. Absolutely not reflecting a bitter flame rising inside, like bile fluttering in his throat. "Shouldn't you've been asking that two bloody years ago, huh? Or wait... you never ever should do something, right?"
The same bitterness is almost material in his voice. And it's like a timer ticking down to zero.

Two years later Moran is still same hard as nails, and his reaction is quick enough that JM can't block a movement of his arm. Slender but strong fingers seize JM by the collar at a flash, a motion so smooth that both cups on the table don't spill a drop.
"You fucking selfish moron," Sebastian hisses, feeling he's getting short of breath, "playing your fucking games, thinking you can come back like nothing happened?"

An inch higher, and this grip of steel could easily strangle, and it's very doubtful Moriarty could effectively resist it, but that hand doesn't move up. Moran is capable of choking JM to death but that doesn't mean he actually can.
"Give me a reason," Sebastian hisses, and it's a white flag already. They both know it.</p>`
};

pagesData[12] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>JM can't help but flinch, not expecting the attack, and end up staring at Moran with an expression full of surprise, as innocent as a cat caught stealing cookies. Now Sebastian's hand is holding him firmly in a position bent over the table. JM tries to pull himself out unenthusiastically, testing the grip rather than really attempting to break free. When he realizes he can't do it, he looks back at Moran with eyes that a girl might give you right after you first kissed her.</p>
<p>"Give me a reason, is this your wish? Haven't I already given you plenty? Too bad you aren't able to use them... Or are you?"</p>
<p>It's easy to imagine Sebastian's hands on his neck, pressing hard enough to sink to the beating artery. JM thinks about how Moran would choke him to death and he wouldn't resist but caress his firm forearms, which are delightfully muscular, while his own face would be swelling with blood, turning red and then blue. Would he look pretty? Would Sebastian tell him he looks pretty? The vivid picture of this perversion makes him lick his lips and swallow nervously.</p>
<p>Moran's eyes, staring back at him without blinking, are the eyes of a murderer, burning with the cold fury that indicates deadly decisiveness. JM wishes to push him further, although he probably must stop now. He can't decide whether he must stop...</p>
<p>"Fuck, I missed seeing you like this," he says under his breath while scratching on Moran's flexed forearm gently. "Just don't ruin my shirt please, thanks."</p>`
};

pagesData[13] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>The attempts Moriarty makes to let go look just like a little mockery. Moran might have that muscles of steel, that iron will and self-control, yet even strongest metals can be broken. For example, when exposed to something toxic. No doubts JM in some ways is more toxic than any acid; and well, sadly, but Moran is still alive and he's not an unfeeling machine – despite what some people think.</p>
JM knows that perfectly well.</p>
<p>That touch of him, almost playful, that innocent look on his face, it hits like a freaking huge amount of volts.</p>
<p>A second before action, Moran knows he'd have to pay for every move and every word. It always was like that, and goddammit, let it be again 'til the end of times. That's something wicked, totally wrong, poisonous and sick, but that's something he desperately needs.</p>
<p>Sebastian knows it when he lets go only to use that false moment of freedom to hit hard and with a great precision.</p>
<p>Sleepy boy at the counter jumps up, awaking immediately when one of his early visitors looks like he's going to kill the other one with his bare hands.</p>
<p>"Don't you even dare," Moran growls at the boy when he's trying to reach his phone, and poor thing just freezes in fear.</p>
<p>Last time something like this happened few years ago, and well– civcas happens.</p>

<p>Sebastian feels a bit dizzy when pressing JM to the nearest wall because too many memories arise immediately. His hand still don't shake, holding that devil's bastard with absolute strength and perfectly careful at the same time. It's more a stare down than an actual treat. It's a duel where Moran knows he'd lose, and yet he never gives up without a fight.</p>
<p>Too fucking many memories. His body can almost feel it.</p>
<p>They are so close right now that he can feel warmth of the body and touch of the breath; it suddenly sends shivers, and Moran reflexively places his hand to the wall as if searching for some support. It gives Moriarty some freedom of movements, but hell with that. Moran feels himself on the verge of a mental breakdown, first for the last five or so years.</p>
<p>He really wants to kill JM with his own hands. And even more he wants him to live; lost in that inner storm which just turns him inside out, Moran closes his eyes for a few seconds. And he thinks that if JM would finally decide to harvest a rabid dog– or rather, rabid tiger– it wouldn't be such bad.</p>
<p>The worst is that he really needs this genius freak, no matter what thar bastard is going to say or do, and yes, Moran knows he'd regret but he cannot care anymore.</p>`
};

pagesData[14] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>The punch in the face took JM unguarded and he would flip over right with his damn chair if it wasn't for Moran who grabbed him once again just to smash against the wall.</p>
<p>When his spine violently meets the brick surface, a helpless groan escapes his mouth – the noise of air leaving his lungs in one thrust.</p>
<p>As soon as Moran gives him a chance, there's a barrel of a gun pressing into his lower abdomen.</p>
<p>There's silence for a moment. And then there's Moriarty's laugh, starting wheezy but growing into something mocking and triumphant.</p>
<p>"Oh you missed me," he laughs, trying to keep his eyes on Sebastian's face despite them involuntarily rolling into his skull from pain mixed with twisted pleasure. "You fucking missed me."</p> 
<p>The bartender is a young boy but he takes his work pretty seriously, so he tells them to take this outside, and eventually Moran has to drag Moriarty, who's kicking and giggling, to the emergency exit (carefully  so that the gun doesn't fire on accident).</p>
<p>Once they're in the privacy of the backyards, it's time to reconsider the distribution of forces, and the 0.33 pointing at Moran seems to be overpowering.</p>
<p>Sometimes JM tends to get overexcited, and clearly he's in one of these states, leaning closer to Sebastian and whispering some endlessly sick dirtytalk in his ear, begging to punch him once more.</p>
<p>"C'mon, tough guy, do it," he hisses, smudging Sebastian's temple with blood from his split lower lip. "I know you want it, I know you hate me, show me how much you hate me-"</p>
<p>However, it's Moran who's pressed against the wall now, and the barrel travels his body, first poking at his stomach, then the ribcage, then his chest, gradually making its way higher and higher...</p>
<p>"I know you want it, I know you want it..."</p>
It appears like JM lulls down his own insanity with this little mantra, until the tip of the gun is pressed under Sebastian's chin.</p> 
Then JM falls silent as if struck with an idea and, in this intimate silence accompanied only with noise of his nervous swallowing, slowly pushes the tip of his handgun into Sebastian's mouth.</p>`
};

pagesData[15] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>It’s almost cinematographic. A barrel of a gun along with a laugh, so out of place yet feeling so right. Trembling but demanding voice of the coffeeshop boy. The moment when Moran drags JM towards the emergency exit, doing it with professional neatness yet still too careful (and it’s not only about the gun). The next moment when that scared but so brave boy throws out a heavy bag containing rifle and stuff, and closes the door immediately with a metal click of the lock. That’s so fucking theatrical as if they all are just going through some well-written playscript.</p>
<p>Maybe it’s true. Maybe Moran really missed him. He won’t admit that though right now, even to himself; but on the other hand— that’s not the most important thing right now.</p>
<p>He knew he’d lost at the very first moment that dark eyes stared right into his icy blue-gray eyes, or rather straigth into his soul. So a dangerous feeling of a gun slowly moving up his body seems kind of appropriate now. First reflex is to freeze in place, assessing the situation; Moran knows he can actually seize the moment and knock the gun from JM’s hands.</p>
He doesn’t do it, losing his breath for a couple of seconds while velvet whisper touches his ear.</p>
<p>In good old Shakespeare-like plays there’s often a poison poured into the ear. A beautiful figure along with a savage act. Feels very right at that exact moment.</p>
<p>Moran still doesn’t move. Not because he’s really afraid of the shot— oh c’mon, death is his good old pal for too many years now. He misses the moment when he can’t really get safe anymore: the higher the gun goes, the less chances he has. The safety’s off so it’s just a question of a moment to pull the trigger and blow his lungs, or his heart, or his brain out.</p>
<p>His heart skips a beat when the barrel touched his chin. Lips feel completely dry, and when the cold metal touches them, somewhere deep inside Moran knows his white flag was accepted right now.</p>
<p>It’s just the life instinct, right? When somebody points a gun and you don’t have a chance to change it, be nice and obedient so you could live?</p>
<p>Well, he lost that fucking chance deliberately, letting that instinct cry in agony.</p>
<p>Dry lips open a bit more when the barrel pushed them almost gently. A perfect pervert allusion. It tastes with metal on the tip of the tongue, and that metal is reflected in Moran’s eyes while he cannot shift his gaze away from JM. The gun pushes a bit deeper meeting no resistance.</p>
<p>That’s very fucking bad. That's fucking total defeat. That’s a fucking mortal threat.
And here and now, that is so fucking right.</p>
<p>I hate you, Moran doesn’t say but it could be read so clearly in his eyes. I fucking hate you, and I did miss you, you bloody bastard.</p>`
};

pagesData[16] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>Staring back at him from inches away, his lips slightly agape, JM seems enchanted with the wordless emotion vibrating in the steel-colored eyes. It feels good being able to finally connect to Sebastian's mind this directly, like a virus which broke through the firewall and installed itself into the software to mess with its digital DNA.</p>
<p>Synchronize. This is what he could never achieve with Sherlock, even though he believed that the only two geniuses of their kind should be able to communicate without the obstruction of language but by inducing their insanity onto each other.</p>
<p>He moves the handgun inside of Moran's mouth in a slow and strangely sensual way as if he can feel the softness of it with his flesh; making his cheeks stretch from the inside with the delicate push of its cold metal tip. Maybe genius is not the only sex; maybe there's also loyalty that can make two minds intertwine.</p>
<p>And also, taking over somebody after a good tackle feels fucking fantastic.</p>
<p>If the barrel was a shaft, then its climax would be it going off. But JM feels his restlessness being soothed and pacified with every thrust of the barrel. And the way Moran's lips, usually thin and pursed together tightly, get softer and more pliant, makes it comparable to some kind of a deflowering.</p>
<p>Shit, he's gonna... If he could only...</p>
<p>JM pulls it out, making the corner of Sebastian's mouth stretch somewhat painfully. Then his hand holding the gun hangs down lifelessly as he leans against Moran's body, burying his face in his shoulder and almost drooling on his jacket, feeling hot in the face and heavy in the head; orgasmic and exhausted by the nervous strain.</p>`
};

pagesData[17] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>Gun metal feels cold and dangerous, and feel absolutely not normal; it's not only because it's a freaking mortal danger to have a loaded gun in the mouth. It's much more because of the memories; because Moran saw the moment JM committed his bloody suicide up there on the roof.</p>
Fake suicide, but it took two years to learn that. Or maybe it's some goddamn miracle, it doesn't matter anymore. Good there's a wall behind the back, because Moran feels like his legs can give way any moment.</p>
<p>The gun slowly goes all way out of his mouth, letting catch some breath back– because Moran was compulsively holding it. Moran doesn't move when he feels the warmth of the body leaning to him.</p>
<p>He only raises his hand mechanically first to put the gun back to safety even not taking it out of JM's hands.</p>
<p>Inside he's shaking, inside it's a true fucking mental breakdown. Outside it's just interrupted, shallow breath.</p>
<p>Then Moran raises his hand again, this time to touch Moriarty's shoulder softly. Not many people could tell that he actually can be so careful and even gentle, yet JM knows that perfectly.</p>
<p>"I still hate you, you know," he says quietly. "But it's not bad to know you're alive."</p>`
};

pagesData[18] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>At the sensation of a gentle touch on his shoulder, JM lifts his head to stare up at Sebastian, hardly realizing that his own face is a mess because there's already a bruise swelling on the side where that punch had landed. Nothing that wouldn't be gone in a week though, and the duality of Sebastian's hands amaze him. Perhaps, he used to take it for granted being carried around like some crystal vase, forgetting those were actually the paws of a tiger that would turn soft for JM only.</p>
<p>Who else could hold him like this? Firmly but carefully enough so that not to break (sometimes JM seemed very breakable), protecting his safety at all costs even at times when strangling him with one's bare hands is something that anybody would want?</p>
<p>Sebastian is the one person JM doesn't have to blackmail or hypnotize into loyalty. This is probably what allowed the two of them to get so close in the first place.</p>
<p>Moriarty can read between the lines of "I hate you", because Sebastian cannot pronounce the simple truth; perhaps he cannot even fully admit it to himself even though there's only one word he'd need to replace for this. So JM stares at him knowingly, keeping his face just inches away from Sebastian's.</p>
<p>But this little moment of intimacy doesn't prove anything yet.</p>
<p>"Seems like you wanted to know this too fucking bad," he whispers softly as if his words weren't a knife preparing to stab. "How well do you remember what happened two years ago?"</p>
<p>His hand sneaks into his pocket to reach for a gum and wanders dangerously close to Sebastian's crotch for several unbearable seconds before getting the chunk. Then JM unwraps it and continues, chewing, breathing minty breath on Sebastian's face.</p> 
<p>"Do you remember how you failed me that day? You were instructed to leave the location immediately, but you hesitated. Why did you, Moran? Were you hoping to see my dead body?"</p>`
};

pagesData[19] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>The facade is quite fragile right now. It takes all the self-control to stay at least visibly calm, no matter what storm rages inside.</p>
Sebastian keeps silence, frowning a bit when JM asks so dangerously softly about the past. Oh, he remembers that perfectly. Every fucking minute of that bloody day two years ago.</p>
<p>He says nothing, letting Moriarty do and say whatever he wants. They are still too close, and every movement just adds fuel to the flames burning from the inside.</p>
<p>And well, not so many things can mortify Moran's pride. But of course JM perfectly knows all the joints in his armour, and after a very short silence he hits– not with a fist but with words which can be the same painful.</p>
<p>Moran's eyes immediately turn colder, he straightens unconsciously, squaring shoulders.
"I did my task," he says dryly in a low voice. "From cover to cover. And the moment I finished, you were dead. I take no orders from dead men."</p>
<p>That mint smell makes him feeling a bit sick. Too familiar, too personal. Too bright. Moran hates chewing gums, at least right at this moment, yet his voice is same perfectly non-emotional.</p>
<p>"And I fucking saw your dead body."</p>
<p>Moran really regrets it– no matter is JM dead or alive, the moment of his suicide and the look of his dead body was something he wished he would never saw. Yet he did, and that image haunted him last two years.</p>
<p>And right now he has no fucking idea how this weird conversation will finish. He's not sure why, he's not sure if he should survive it; he's not sure if he wants to.</p>`
};

pagesData[20] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>"Did you? Hmmm," he cocks his head skeptically. "Do I look like a zombie to you, then? A ghost?"</p>
<p>He inspects Moran closely, almost like a bootcamp instructor inspects a marine corp recruit, except it's worse since his voice is so quiet, great danger lurking behind it. Actually, JM would be more like a commanding officer to him, since the price of disobeying a commanding officer is way higher. This whole conversation doesn't appear as some tantrum from a hysterical lover – it's a talk of disappointment from an authority figure.</p>
<p>JM is waiting for signs of a breakdown in Sebastian's face – maybe, his lips would tremble, eyes become wet – but he is a tough one, gotta give him the credit, and aside from his stiff expression there's nothing.</p>
<p>How could Moriarty possibly know, that two years ago Sebastian Moran hesitated for a little longer than needed before aborting the operation according to the pre-provided instructions, just because he couldn't believe what he witnessed and stayed to see the irrefutable evidence of JM's death? And, since everything happened in a haze, how long the delay must have really taken? Two instants?</p>
<p>If he saw JM lifeless body, how is it possible that right now he's pressing Sebastian against the wall in the backyards of some cafeteria, tickling him with his breath, their lips almost touching?</p>
<p>Memory is a funny thing sometimes; you can't really trust it. But, again, you can't really trust Jim Moriarty, because he's a nasty little liar.</p>
<p>Even though it seems impossible, JM leans even closer, slowly, like in some weird dream. Then he whispers:</p>
<p>"You must never fail me again. Prove you're still the best shot in London." He brings the gum wrapper next to Sebastian's eyes and there's something written on it in microscopic letters – time and address. JM puts it in his palm and steps back.</p>
<p>Then the gun goes off as JM fucking shoots the door lock open and walks out.</p>`
};

pagesData[21] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>You do look like a delusion, Moran thinks yet says nothing. Of course he says nothing, always playing a role of a silent shadow behind JM’s shoulder. So he’s the same right now; and also, he has to keep silence because it’s the only way for him now to keep a straight face. It takes all the willpower and concentration right now.</p>
<p>Velvet, soft whisper sounds of pure danger. Inner air raid siren howls horrified, but Moran doesn’t let if reflect in his eyes. JM’s fucking dangerous. Always was; and seems like always will be. He could simply cross out any name, names, maybe nations, hell knows, and sometimes death could be actually the best way out of it. Moran knows his ways; moreover, he participated so often. And now it’s him who’s in the crosshairs.</p>
<p>Two years ago, he had like a second or two to see the dead body. Or what he thought was a dead body. Because then he had to get his work done, and so he did. He takes no orders from dead men, but he fulfilled an order given before death.
Yet now he’s absolutely fucking sure that it is JM, beucase no fucking person in the whole bloody world could copy him so well.</p>
<p>He keeps bloody calm all the way. He doesn't let himself shiver even a bit when that fucking gum wrap comes into his hand. He doesn't wince when JM uses a gun to leave the backyard.</p>
<p>Once the not-so-dead-man leaves, he keeps hid facade for few more seconds. And then, exhaling some curses almost soundless, Moran lets himself a weakness.</p>
<p>He spends freaking long couple of minutes sitting right here on the ground in some backyard, shivering in silent breakdown, until the coffeeshop boy peeks out.</p>
<p>"Are you alright, sir?" he says, his voice skeptical as if he has a whole bobby squad behind him. Moran knows there isn't.</p>
<p>He's absolutely not alright.</p>
<p>"Shit happens," he says getting up and picking his bag, immediately gathering himself up. And simply walks out, feeling the boy's cautious sight in his back.</p>
<p>Well, no bobbies, no troubles.</p>
<p>There's a storm raging inside. There's a shitload of bile rising up to the throat. There's a fucking wrap with tiny letters, and goddamn, sometimes Moran hates himself for being able to do almost everything JM wants, 'cos he can read this inscription easily.</p>
<p>So he does; and it's actually today's evening. He has kind of thirteen hours before he shall be at the position. It's a very bad joke, since the position shall be absolutely the same he took when first worked for JM, before even knowing it's JM.</p>
<p>The address is not the same, yet the perfect point for a sniper is the same, and Moriarty knows that for sure.</p>
<p>Moran doesn't remember how he gets back home; neither he remembers how he spends few hours.</p>
<p>He comes around at quarter past three. Head bit dizzy, heartbeat sinuous. The only one material evidence from the morning is that bloody gum wrap.</p>
<p>Two hours later, Moran feels like he's maybe walking a nightmarish dream when he goes up to the roof of a big business centre, unnoticed. Noone pays attention at a well-dressed mad with an expensive looking club bag; many white collars go for a business trip right from their offices, or return same way.</p>
<p>It's all so routine. Go up, make sure CCTV doesn't see you, walk the closed service path, take a good place which gives a perfect view. Actually, at this moment Moran's not sure if it's not his mind playing tricks on him, but whatever. If he's insane, he's insane, so hell with that.
The only one thing he can believe in this whole fucking world is a rifle; and he leans to one of his 'girls' holding it gently like a lover, looking through the sight in search of his victim.</p>
<p>Such a routine.</p>
<p>The distance is too high for almost anyone; that distance is fine with Moran– well, JM always wanted the impossible, and Moran always could do the impossible. Perfect interaction, isn't it?</p>
<p>Yet Sebastian knows he has to prove he's still the same old best one. No matter if it's only his insanity or not, first he would act– then he would think.</p>`
};

pagesData[22] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>This business complex looks like a bunch of weirdly composed glass towers, 30+ floor each. Now that Moran is on the roof, he's surrounded with windows, that are mirroring the clouds violently racing in the evening sky; red beacons for aviation light; and a huge neon sign with running text saying it's the best premium bank for crypto investment using high-tech instruments, which provide top-level security for the transactions. This and the sun at the golden hour makes the whole complex glow.</p>
<p>At 6 PM people are already leaving their offices. Down there, they look like ants.</p>
<p>The weird thing is: Sebastian doesn't have the description if his target yet. Who is he supposed to search for, which window aim at? There's always been some level of mystery with Moriarty and the instructions could follow any moment now. In a minute Sebastian's phone would ring with an incoming message, perhaps.</p>
<p>6:10 PM and there's still nothing. It's getting harder to stay motionless since the wind is chilly.</p>
<p>Behind the windows, there are people working late in their offices or attending meetings in the conference rooms. Maybe it's gonna be one of the businessmen, who are sitting at the head of long tables reviewing visual presentations on some P&L reports?</p>
<p>The higher the floor, the more it looks like there're technical spaces and utility rooms. Data centers are lined in an endless row.</p>
<p>And at the top of the tower, covered with a rather flimsy glass dome, there seems to be a slowly rotating satellite dish, probably for transmitting data.</p>
<p>Then the light of the setting sun hits this glass dome at a special angle and a strange vision uncovers itself to Sebastain's view, yet it looks weirdly familiar: a smiley face painted with a red spray. It looks mischievous, with crosses instead of eyes, and a target on its forehead.</p>
<p>Is it possible that this whole operation didn't involve a human target in the first place? And what Sebastian's really supposed to do is way more tech-oriented, like causing some kind of a digital lock down to enforce the hacker heist designed by Moriarty?</p>
<p>He finally receives an anonymous text message, saying only:</p>
<p>*>:) make me rich baby*</p>`
};

pagesData[23] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>It’s actually not the first time Moran receives details only on-site. With JM, that would happen maybe not often but regularly enough to get used. Time and place; and then, an additional message would come. Or sometimes a call.</p>
<p>That’s why when positioning himself at the chosen spot, Moran takes out his phone placing it such way so he could easily see any message or incoming call. And then, he waits.</p>
<p>A good sniper shall be very, very patient. They shall be able to stay motionless for long hours, waiting for their target, sometimes even for a day or two. Moran’s longest was almost forty-six hours plus two hours he had to wait so he can safely leave. His body was all numb that time, and he really hated the experience.</p>
<p>With JM, his longest was bit more than seven hours. The target was not so predictable, so he had to wait while other Moriarty’s people were working like hounds. It was really well-played, though then Moran couldn’t get warm for freaking few hours no matter what he did.</p>
<p>This time it’s not so cold. It windy, noisy and very usual. Or maybe it is cold but Sebastian doesn’t feel it. He watches around, sometimes through the sight, sometimes just with his own eyes; except of really slight head movements, he’s keeping perfectly still and motionless.</p>
<p>And then, a work of art shows itself. A weird art maybe, street or modern one, or maybe it’s even a whole performance.</p>
<p>He might be absolutely motionless now yet Moran’s mind runs really fast now. It takes maybe a couple of seconds to get a complete grasp. And well, the task is quite elaborate since it’s not only about distance.</p>
<p>A good shot means a great amount of very quick calculations. Everything shall be taken into account: the distance, the wind, the light, the movements, the size of a target, and so on. Right now Moran would say his chance of success is somewhere around three out of ten, since the sunlight and the wind are quite harsh. Plus, that freaking dome would mess into shell path. Oh well, Moran always likes a good challenge.</p>
<p>He takes few more seconds to check the target. It rotates, so he has to take this into account in order to destroy it properly. Then, he leans closer to the rifle, heartbeat perfectly steady, breath perfectly slow and deep.</p>
<p>Right now Moran resembles a statue. Absolutely still, he’s waiting for a perfect moment, and a moment before that moment he gently pulls the trigger when exhaling.</p>
<p>The bullet covers that distance in almost two seconds, hitting the dome violently and then hitting the target right at the moment when it rotates up to the ideal positioning.
A beautiful and clean shot.</p>
<p>In films, the shooter quickly gets up and run away right after. In reality, Moran keeps the same perfect motionless posture, checking through the sight the spots from where his own is seen. A military habit actually, since too many people were vanished after a good shot just because they wanted to go away too quickly. Maybe there’s no need in these circumstances, yet he still waits a bit.</p>
<p>A couple of times, he would receive a new message right after, giving one more target or something else. More often, he would receive nothing for a couple of days.</p>`
};

pagesData[24] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>As soon as the target is hit, there's a glitch going throughout the building causing the lights to go off for a moment, but then it returns to normal. The alarm is silent. It's gonna take several business days to notice that something is wrong, but the financial data is already leaking, re-routed for withdrawal through the fake protocols and convoluted proxy chains.</p>
<p>And when they do notice, the organization is gonna get into big trouble on the stock market, allowing one of Moriarty's ghost companies to incorporate it almost for free and milk it fucking dry.</p>
<p>JM is probably watching his screen go mad from notifications right now. And it's quite the start for reviving his operations and getting back into business after the two years of laying low. Surely, he didn't spend them doing completely nothing, but his positions of power need to be reinforced, especially after the Holmes brothers worked on dismantling his network.</p>
<p>And, being honest to oneself, his power play with Sherlock even before the Reichenbach costed him a lot, not to mention the final forced march when he practically decided to go all-in.</p>
<p>Sebastian's phone lights up again and there're several text messages coming in a row:</p>
<p>*now that was a sexy one!*</p>
<p>*why freeze your balls off up there? you wanna do some shootin for sport?*</p>
