<p>Just a tease here 'cus JM knows Sebastian wouldn't do shit without a direct order.</p>
<p>Years ago, when he was studying Sebastian's personnel file, his ability to hold the position for days couldn't go unnoticed. JM still hopes to make him beat that 48-hour motionless score, just because he likes scores being beaten for him. But today there's no real need for this, and upon Sebastian's return home he'll be pleased to find his little taste of the money left on his pillow along with a cute note from JM saying: "welcome back".</p>
<p>And by the dirty mug half-full with tea remaining on the table Sebastian will know for sure that JM himself has visited his place, while he was away on the mission. 
JM was curious enough to examine his room and his stuff, even rest on his bed for a little, wondering how Moran had been living for two years.</p>
<p>But, again, by the moment Sebastian returns, he's already gone.</p>`
};

pagesData[25] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>For few minutes, absolutely nothing happens. Then, a few messages appear meaning that Moran can leave the spot, and he takes a bit of time to stretch himself and then carefully pack all the stuff back into his club bag, then takes a bit of time to escape the omnipresent CCTV, and finally he gets out of the building, looking like a serious white collar who works overtime a lot. Security at the entrance doesn't even look at him, and that is actually like it should be after all the preparations.</p>
<p>He freezes at the door of his apartment. A nice, not big yet expensive one in Knightsbridge– it's just a couple of rooms but he could exchange it for a nice 2-story house somewhere in the close suburbs. He prefers to stay in the centre though.</p>
<p>The lock is not in the position he left it. So Moran takes out a handgun along with keys, opening the door carefully. He steps inside and freezes again, listening. Nothing.</p>
<p>His small yet quite fancy flat looks neat enough, though for sure there's some nice little chaos like unwashed dishes or some clothes on the chair in the bedroom; few souvenirs in the living room mark he's been to India and Iraq a lot, and also visited some Latin American places. There's dust somewhere, there are some books that look used and some that look absolutely new, but all in all– this flat reflexes him. Neat, composed, sturdy framed yet a bit sentimental and alive. Still fucking alive.</p>
<p>Moran places his bag down in the bedroom, looking at the money and note left on his pillow. Not touching it yet, he goes to the kitchen to get some water because his throat feels dry like he swallowed some sand.</p>
<p>And then, there's a mug with some tea left.</p>
<p>It takes time to recompose himself again.</p>
<p>Few years ago when he just started to work for JM, he'd found a hidden camera by a pure accident– more like thanks to the crazy neighbour and his crazy houseworks. That time, Moran didn't show he noticed it, but searched for more inconspicuously. And there were five of them; he experimented by covering those cameras 'accidentaly' and wasn't sure if there are just those five.</p>
<p>One day when he came back home being away for a couple of days and being literally by Moriarty's side all that time, the cameras were gone.</p>
<p>Moran changed his locks after that, knowing it won't help.</p>
<p>Also, he changed his locks a month ago, just because there was some unpleasant experience for his neighbours; and his house is elite enough to have CCTV in elevator and stairs. Well, he's sure it didn't work today for some mysterious reason.</p>
<p>Moran keeps calm while washing the dishes, while taking shower, collecting the money left on the pillow, taking the note out to the balcony where he takes a cigarette and burns the note down.</p>
<p>An hour later, something breaks inside. Sound of porcelain crashing into the wall doesn't help, and not there's a faint beige spot on the wall, but Sebastian doesn't care.
And he feels himself completely lost in own feelings.</p>`
};

pagesData[26] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>JM has always liked Sebastian's apartment, its neatly styled modernity filled with memorable things that gave it its character and made the rooms look inhabited. From the balcony, across the nearby street bustling with people flowing the luxury boutiques, you could usually see the green alleys of the Hyde Park and how they would become illuminate with colorful lanterns in the evening. It was peaceful rather than boring, as if you were the lone observer, always towering above someone else's busy and ordinary lives.</p> 
<p>JM used to love staying over sometimes. He liked that the apartment smelled nice and that it wasn't stuffy, like Sherlock's, yet he always had something to go through: the books, the foreign souvenirs, Sebastian's personal belongings related to the army, like his military awards or personal badge. There was hardly anything there that he hadn't examined at some point, though while Sebastian was away executing that digital crypto heist for JM, he came to the empty apartment in search of something special – something that would actually define the next task for Sebastian Moran.</p>
<p>The old photos from Sebastian's military service in Iraq. He already looks very hardened in those, but younger and yet unknowing of the fact that one day he will be poisoned with JM's toxic influence.</p>
<p>JM almost felt sentimental while looking at those, caressing them with his fingers. However, as much as he enjoyed looking at Moran's cute face, the sniper alone wasn't JM's person of interest this time.</p>
<p>Once upon a time, there was a man who served alongside Moran in Iraq until their paths diverged. His name was Cormac Thompson, and he made it pretty high to the ranks, even being a field commander to Sebastian at some point, until an injury made him transfer from the hot spots to more political oriented duties and eventually become a Deputy Director of National Security Strategy; now retired in his mansion in the suburbs.</p>
<p>What nobody knows is: Cormac Thompson fell a victim to the same monster, who had been using him for years. Maybe he hoped it would stop after his retirement and Moriarty's death; and it probably would, if JM would stay gone forever and if he himself wouldn't become a problem.</p>
<p>Now JM was holding the photo of Sebastian and Cormac together. He made a copy of it with his phone and put everything back in its place, though it wouldn't matter if Sebastian'd notice. JM left some mess for him to notice anyway.</p>
<p>The excitement almost made him hard. And the room, the smell of it; and the younger version of Sebastian, looking at him from the old picture. It felt so familiar that JM considered lounging on Sebastian's bed for a little more and jerk off, maybe, but the time was too limited.</p>

<p>And so he was gone, leaving behind a ghost of his presence that would disturb Sebastian's dreams the following night.</p>
<p>JM didn't contact Moran for three days. Was it all a dream? The papers were silent. Nobody knew that something was happening.</p>
<p>Then Sebastian got a message, saying:</p>
<p>*I need you to meet an old friend of ours.*</p>
<p>*he's causing me PROBLEMS. go talk to him.*</p>
<p>*tell him I'm back and can kick his ass.*</p>
<p>Two files attached. First, the picture of Sebastian and Cormac during their military service in Iraq. Second, the recent headlines: "TOP MANAGER IN CHARGE OF NATIONAL SECURITY SUED! Cormac Thompson, the retired Deputy Director of National Security Strategy, is now being accused of selling sensitive data. The FBI suspects he might be connected to the criminal organization of James Moriarty, which stays active even after the presumable death of its leader. Will he cooperate?"</p>
<p>No address given, because Moran can find it himself, surely.</p>`
