pagesData[27] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>It takes whole evening and half of night to pull himself together. Yet the rest of the night doesn’t bring peace. Nightmares are very often guests last years, yet this time it’s something else. Moran wakes up quite early, feeling exhausted and haunted. Inner paranoia is alarmed, as if there’s something dangerous closely— or rather, somebody.
It takes one more day and night to rethink everything happened, and well, might be it would be great to find out it’s all just vivid imagination, yet there is some evidence. For example, like a very slight pain in the corner of mouth caused by tiny scratch. This scratch still feels with a taste of cold gun metal and hot breath in a velvet whisper.</p>
<p>It takes an evening in attempt to get fucking drunk and let himself forget about everything at least for a night, when Moran goes out to get some whiskey in a fancy liquor store nearby. Yet nothing goes well: he’s still sober after a whole bottle, just feeling predictably sick but with an absolutely clear mind. Bad idea, but well, he tried.</p>
<p>It takes the next day to pull himself together once again and check everything he can. This time no real evidence, yet Moran is rather observant and attentive to notice some tiny details speaking loudly for somebody who knows JM’s style of work.</p>
<p>And well, Moran knows. Much more than a usual sniper should; though he was a ‘usual sniper’ just for a while, then slowly and unwittingly making his way up. He knew a lot of things noone knew, he was told some things Moriarty wouldn’t tell anyone else, he even had a right to argue sometimes, explicitly saying JM some of his plans are bullshit for reasons.</p>
<p>His phone is silent, his usual way to contact don’t work anymore. All Sebastian has to do is to wait, and at least he can do it perfectly well.</p>
<p>When his phone suddenly comes alive with a row of messages, Moran is at least calm enough finally. A little deal with own self: he pretends it’s all fine like there were no last two years, and his underconsciousness gives him a delay for a new mental breakdown. Nice, innit.</p>
<p>And the task is actually so well-known in style.</p>
<p>When Cormac Thompson walks out of his residence, using back door and walking quickly, he’s stopped by a calm and even somewhat cordial voice: "Whatever you’re doing, stop." He rounds on a sound just to find his comrade-in-arms leaning to the fence, smoking lazily and slightly smiling.</p>
<p>"Crap, if my eyes don’t cheat me. Old tricks again? Coming out of nowhere with your stupid jokes?"</p>
<p>Moran gives a short warm laugh, trowing aside unfinished cigarette and saluting casually. "Won’t say it’s a joke. Care for a drink, mate?"</p>
<p>Something in his eyes makes Cormac understand it's not just a sudden nostalgia that made Moran come here and meet him after so many years. Though they used to be almost friends in the past, their paths went very different. And through this lazy and casual attitude, some danger is seen, so Cormac, being all nerves last couple of days, just nods.</p>
<p>Bit later they sit in a nearby pub, in a cozy corner where walls are decorated with football club scarves and some old posters. Thompson is drumming his fingers on his glass of lager, while Moran seems completely calm and even somewhat enjoying his stout.</p>
<p>"So. If not a joke, than what?" Cormac says slowly after a nice small talk a two old comrades shall have.</p>
<p>"Take it as it is," Moran shrugs and then takes a folded newspaper out of his inner pocket, placing in between them. The same headliner Mortiarty sent him earlier. "I mean what I mean, mate. Stop."</p>
<p>Cormac straightens himself a bit, looking colder now and sipping his beer just to gain few seconds to think.</p>
<p>"You know nothing, mate," he says finally. "I’ve no idea why-"</p>
<p>"I know much better than you think," Moran says in a low velvety voice, interrupring him.</p>
<p>"Listen, Thompson. I hate to say twice so I’ll say once. Stop it. At this moment, you’re still kinda safe and sound, but just one snap, and you’re not. Don’t you even think that you can play tricks with JM."</p>
<p>"He’s dead," Cormac says quickly as if he was ready to say it at any moment.</p>
<p>"You sure?" Sebastian lets himself a smile, and that smile isn’t something friendly— it signals of a calm, composed menace, of a known fact, and of a danger.</p>
<p>"The hell you know."</p>
<p>"Oh. I do know the hell, mate," Moran leans a little bit closer, still same calm and casual.</p>
<p>"I bet you won’t like it. So take it as a friendly advice. Stop it now. Be a good boy. Keep calm and carry on. Believe me, no government can show you such hell."</p>
<p>"You worked for him," Cormac says after a pause. "Are you working under his name now? Is that your idea to take over?"</p>
<p>"Mate," Moran sounds almost disappointed. "Really? Listen, I’m here to save your bloody arse. Show some respect to my words, huh? I’m telling you how to survive actually."</p>
<p>And then, there’s a quiet metal click under the table. Cormac’s face goes white because he knows this sound too well. They both know. He can see a genuine pity in Moran’s eyes yet he knows that Moran’s gun is pointing somewhere. Maybe a knee, maybe a foot, maybe his crotch. He always was the best shooter he knew, so it won’t be a deal for him to make a perfect shot even not aiming.</p>
<p>"Don’t you dare." still says Cormac.</p>
<p>"I do dare," Moran says almost politely. "Now, mate, I would love to hear the right words from you... please."</p>
<p>This politeness is just a kind of a game; Thompson can feel himself a rabbit caught in the corner by a big wild cat who’s going to play first before killing. And that cat won’t even eat its prey, because no need to.</p>
<p>Few hours later, there’s a message about which Moran isn’t sure if it will reach the recipient.</p>
<p>Thompson won’t be a problem anymore.</p>
<p>Sending it, Moran feels a desperate need to at least hear something, but he manages not to push the 'call' button.</p>
<p>No, dammit. He shouldn't feel such shit. He hates JM and shall hate him no matter what...
...and he's fucking in dire need of anything: a voice, a glance, a touch, a praise or a displeasure expressed. Just fucking anything real because he's going insane.</p>`
};

pagesData[28] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>The transition from disbelief to realization on Cormac's face was too vivid, as if one could see him think to himself: "So it's true, then". For a moment there was a resentful disappointment glistening in his eyes, because despite Moran's deceptively friendly attitude, he appeared to be no better than JM himself. Then, when the gun clicked under the table, there was only fear left, again.</p>
<p>"I can't go to jail, Seb," said Cormac with an unusual sadness you can only see in gamblers, who are so deeply in debt that there's almost no way out. "My health is not what it used to be. I'll die there."</p>
<p>After his plea failed to shake Moran's determination, he continued, now observing the foam in his beer keep settling slowly:</p>
<p>"You're wrong about him. If you become a problem, or when he doesn't need you anymore, he'll dump you. Like he's dumping me right now. He's..." Cormac looked at Moran and saw his face completely unresponsive. Then he gave in. "Think about it, at least, for your own sake. Promise you'll think about it. You can tell him I'll stop."</p>
<p>After they were done, Cormac Thompson returned to his mansion, took a revolver from his safe box and shot himself in the head.</p>
<p>In an hour, the housekeeper will find his body and call the police.</p>
<p>And in a couple of hours, the papers will add this to the chronicles of weird events that happened during the last several weeks: deaths or disappearances of highly ranked figures, scams on financial market, unexpected M&A deals.</p>
<p>Now, his funds raised, threats eliminated, pieces lined up on the chessboard, JM is ready for another game. And, since every game should begin with a proper debut, he's already started developing his pieces towards attacking the center – including his most loyal knight.</p>
<p>Moran doesn't get a reply to his message, however, on his way home, a second before he would enter the doorway, he gets an incoming call.</p>
<p>"Hiii. Remember where we first met in person? Come to me... I'm dying to see you."</p>
<p>A terrace overlooking the Hyde Park. Years ago, when Moran was roaming the streets right after his demobilization, he was approached by a man who decided to address his feeling of alienation and said something about how depressing it should feel – watching all those happy wanderers walking through the alleys, knowing nothing about Iraq, war, whatever. "Aren't you jealous of their blissful oblivion? Seems like the world just keeps spinning without you."</p>
<p>That terrace hasn't changed a bit. JM is there, waiting, drinking some beverage through a straw. When Moran arrives, he doesn't greet him with any commentary on the mission, but instead makes a good, long and noisy inhale. "Can you feel it? It smells like rain."</p>
<p>It does, though. The sky is getting gloomy, because a storm cloud is coming their way; "the happy wanderers" start leaving the park, but JM seems unbothered.</p>
<p>"I just really wanted to show you something today..."</p>`
};

pagesData[29] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>The moment they said goodbye out of the pub, Moran knew it’s their last salute. He could feel the sense of death coming– when you meet it too often, you begin to predict it. He knew Cormac won’t survive despite his words before. "I’m sorry, mate," Moran said before leaving.</p>
<p>"No you’re not," Thompson said when he was few steps away already.</p>
<p>For a moment, Sebastian wanted to stop and turn back, and tell his old comrade that he is because they dragged each other from hell, they survived few conflicts, they both knew the price of their lives. But he didn’t– because maybe he really isn’t. There was nothing new in Cormac’s opinion about JM. And no need to promise anything because Moran thought about it too much. He knew he would be dumped as soon as JM won’t need him anymore, yet that changed absolutely nothing already.</p>
<p>Everyone makes their choices, mate.</p>
<p>And maybe he still has a chance to survive despite anything.</p>
<p>An incoming call becomes a surprise, making Moran freeze at place and look at his phone with suspicion. But of course he answers, and the voice he hears sends chills down the spine. It’s rather hard to understand all own emotions; Sebastian doesn’t give an answer yet JM doesn’t wait for it. They both know he’d come.</p>
<p>And so it happens, because Moran perfectly remembers the place. He has a rather good memory but some things he remembers not because of that. He could recite almost every word JM said at their first in-person meeting.</p>
<p>The world kept spinning without him. And actually, it was perfectly spinning without JM as well. World never cared for anyone, yet everyone cared for someone.</p>
<p>Sometimes Moran wondered if JM cares about anyone at all, and then that fucking Sherlock Holmes happened.</p>
<p>"More like storm," he says, taking a place near Moriarty and not looking at him. At least, directly, since his off-centre vision is always focused on JM when he’s around.</p>
<p>Hyde Park is all the same day by day. People pass by, people come and go. People live and fucking die, and one person managed to die but come back– well, the world still doesn’t care, and Hyde Park doesn't, but Moran cares.</p>

<p>"You say it like you changed your mind," Sebastian replies, giving a side look. There’s a momentary desire to grab him by the collar again, throw down on the floor, kick the shit out of him, and strangle with own hands so to be sure he never comes back again. Then, another desire of the same nature, but reversed.</p>
<p>Instead of doing something, Moran lights a cigarette, not caring if it’s permitted here. His hands don’t shake at all, his breath is perfectly steady, but his heartbeat is somewhat unlevel and speedy, and something trembles inside.</p>
<p>It takes all the willpower to stay calm and composed.</p>`
};

pagesData[30] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>There they are, like in the good old days, looking not at each other but in the same direction, like equals: maybe not in the level of grandiosity, since there'll never be an equal to JM except Sherlock who still wouldn't care to scale his brilliance into something larger than 221B Baker Street; but in spirit, profession, you call it. Moran is JM's only real team.</p>
<p>"Maybe I really should keep it for another time, but then it's a duel between being changeable and being impatient. You've always been the patient one. Also... What I wanna show you is actually about 20 minutes away from here, so I'll have to give you one more ride."</p>
<p>Sebastian is correct: what's coming is probably going to be more than just a simple rain, being greater in its cleansing power. The wind is making the trees toss violently, and it's enough to evoke an association with the Flood sent to wipe out all life on Earth. Except this time, perhaps, not everybody will be wiped out – just the last of JM's enemies, standing on the way of his reinstatement.</p>
<p>From their elevated terrace they can see the rain starting to descend upon the distant neighborhoods. JM seems hesitant, while still sipping on his drink, but then he breaks:</p>
<p>"Aah let's fucking go. By the way: the milkshake they serve here? Still slaps."</p>
<p>He calls a cab, and it drives them past the Marble Arch, then temptingly close to Baker Street which is just two blocks eastwards, then past the Regent's park and the Primrose and all the way north to Highgate. The ride takes longer than expected because of traffic, but the further away from the city center, the more it tends to speed up along the lenghty roads, making the two passengers bounce softly on the backseat.</p>
<p>Inside the close interior it's easy to remember how JM would become all clingy with Sebastian in his private cars, especially while on the move: he used to say it excited him. But now he's leaning back on his seat, not looking at Sebastian, perhaps, because he wouldn't really do anything in a taxi.</p>
<p>By the time they arrive at Highgate Cemetery, it's already raining slightly, threatening to get heavier with each minute. JM makes Sebastian follow him deeper and deeper into the victorian part of the cemetery, until they get lost in the green thickets of vines and ferns. JM's real intentions stay mysterious, and right now Sebastian could be going towards being whacked. Maybe there's a hole, a freshly dug grave hidden under the leaves?</p>
<p>(What if the moment when JM stopped needing Moran has already come and he failed to notice?)</p>
<p>The arch to the Egyptian avenue casts a veil of darkness onto the trail. Now there are tombs, mausoleums and columbaria surrounding them, and JM draws Moran's attention to a rather undistinguished ledger stone.</p>
<p>There's an inscription saying "James Moriarty", lived and died in the late 19th century.</p>
<p>"It's not mine, obviously," JM says. "Just a funny coincidence. I stumbled upon it on accident many years ago, and it's kind of my secret place now. And that's pretty much it, the whole surprise. Duh!"</p>
<p>Then he turns to Sebastian pretty much for the first time since their little fight in a coffeeshop. His cheek still looks a bit bruised with the greenish mark that is already fading. "If I ever disappear again, which I don't feel like doing by the way, you may find something you'll probably need in this one."</p>
<p>The rain is getting heavier. JM tugs at Sebastian's jacket for more attention. It's wet, by the way, and they both are soaking wet.</p> 
<p>"I can't take it anymore... How are you doing this? How are you staying so calm?" he whispers, looking at Moran as if he was the tortured one and not the other way around.
Then slowly, as if trying to pet a tiger, he raises his hand and touches Sebastian's face with the base of his palm.</p>`
};

pagesData[31] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>They travel through the city, and Moran still doesn't look at JM yet observes him every moment. There's not much space in cab, and the distance between them is quite tiny. But it at least is. Some part of him wants to eliminate it, some part wants to make it larger.</p>
<p>Moran is really patient. It's just his nature; maybe that's why he's a good sniper. He can wait, and he can do it for a very long time, and he can hide all his emotions deep inside.
It may outcome in a breakdown though, but well, fair price.</p>
<p>It's so cinematographic again. Rain pours down making the city blurry and even more gray; and they are silent while making their way in a cab, then on foot. Rain and cemetery, such a peacockery. JM always was a show off, and damn he could make a great show for anything.</p>
<p>Funny it's Highgate, Moran thinks, because when he dies, he'd be buried exactly here, nearby his ancestors. Or is it time already?</p>
<p>Moriarty is back, and he's going to start a new big game, and maybe he wants to change absolutely everything, starting with a clear state. That would include all new people around as well.</p>
<p>Moran thinks of it as they pass by the graves, not caring of rain, though they don't have umbrellas. Does he fear of death? No. Does he want to die? Hell knows. Does he want to die right now? Absolutely not.</p>
<p>They stop at the grave with same name, when JM tells about it. Moran gives only one look to the grave, then finally shifting his gaze upon Moriarty. His face still has some slight traces of their previous meeting. Sebastian absolutely doesn't regret it, maybe he could give a couple more punches actually.</p>
<p>"Nice," Moran says dryly, and that's all he can say right now, because he feels like something inside is much more of a storm than the weather. That storm can break out any moment, yet the habit makes him keep it calm no matter what.</p>
<p>Something inside breaks though when Moriarty steps closer, touching his jacket. Something bitter, sharp and dangerous, and maybe very weak at the same time.</p>
<p>He lets JM touch his cheek and then in one smooth, perfect movement grabs his wrist. That grip of steel is strangely careful: Sebastian holds his hand steadily and tightly, yet not giving even slightest pain or cramps.</p>
<p>"How? Oh, there's a simple answer," he says low-key, and though his voice is quite tranquil, but his eyes like reflecting the storm in the sky. Or rather, the storm inside. "I stay calm because I know how much you hate it."</p>
<p>Moran gives a small smirk, looking more like a sarcastic grin of a predator seeing its prey. He doesn't lie now actually; he doesn't like to lie prefering silence instead, yet when he needs, he can lie so perfectly that noone would notice.</p>
It feels like time and space don't have any sense right now, like something can happen.</p>
<p>Right now Moran could raise his another hand and easily strangle JM to death, leaving him on the grave of his namesake. He doesn't do it, and he wouldn't, and goddamn JM knows that for sure too.</p>
<p>"So when are you going to dump me, huh?" the grin turns more noticeable, and tone of the voice king of trembling a little bit. "What games are you playing again, James?"</p>
<p>Right now Moran couldn't say what he means. Is it 'let me take part in that games'? Is it 'stop it all at once'? Is it 'leave me alone' or 'please let me stay'?</p>
Maybe it's everything in one.</p>
<p>Maybe if he'd feel something more, like one more touch or even a breath caressing his skin, he will finally break.</p>
<p>Maybe it ends now, but goddammit, please no, because something inside cries to live, and that fucking something also cries to stay by JM's side like it was years before.</p>`
};

pagesData[32] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>JM tries to free his wrist from Moran's grip, again, just to test if he can do this, knowing in advance that he can't and it's perfectly strong. Being an eyewitness of Moran's physical strength never fails to turn him on, specifically when it's used against him, because it feels so bittersweet. He even wouldn't mind being handled more uncaringly, but it's just something Sebastian can't do – be clumsy and disorganized in his motions.</p> 
<p>He stares at Moran expressionless, as if his venomous words, the smug smirk, the audacity made JM's mind go blank while trying to process it, but the dark passion growing hungrier is still lurking in his eyes. He starts smiling too, very weakly, as if mirroring Sebastian without realizing it, but then something pathetic takes over and it looks now more like a smile of a small guilty dog. He doesn't feel guilty though, humbled maybe, and shy for his own rejected attempt at tenderness.</p>
<p>"Oh I do, I do hate it..." JM whispers. He hates being humbled, he hates being rejected, but it always turns into a twisted foreplay with Moran, because being this cruel looks so good on him and because he always knew how to drive JM fucking nuts.</p>
<p>"Where did you even get this idea? Cormac messed with your brain?" he says absent-mindedly, trying to discard the question as usual, while his free hand slides around Sebastian's waist like a snake. When JM's so close, it's noticeable that he is shivering slightly, but it's unclear whether he's cold or just really desperate – probably both since he's soaking wet and Sebastian is the only warmth he can reach for. The almost undetectable tremble in Moran's voice fills JM with ghostly hope for a victory, and then he's close enough to brush Sebastian's cheekbone with the tip of his nose, ready to apply his old tactics all at once: the touching, the trickery, the bargain.</p>
<p>"What games am I playing, huh?" JM murmurs against Sebastian's skin. "You don't believe I just really wanted to see you, take you for a little promenade? By the way, we still have an unfinished business, you and I. Because I promised you one wish, and I still owe it to you, remember?"</p>
<p>He knows he wouldn't be happy with Moran giving in too easily and there's just too much pleasure in trying to figure out a way to sneak into that impregnable fortress, crawl past his defenses, make him yield, while feeling so naughty all the way through. But how long will they play like this? Will JM ever see Sebastian give in and break, fall on his knees maybe, confess how much he missed him? Or will he resist enough to make JM do all this and beg for a little affection?</p>`
};

pagesData[33] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>With every second passing, it's more and more difficult to stay composed. It's more and more about emotions taking over, and well, Moran was never good with his emotions. Right now it feels like there's some shattered glass inside, and it cuts, it makes bleeding, it hurts. It makes him feel he's still alive.</p>
<p>He feels that weird half-embrace, and he could shake it off with his free hand but he doesn't. He lets JM lean closer as if really wanting him to get some warmth. He was always the one with evercold hands, while Moran was like overfilled with the hot sun of Middle East, never leaving him even after retirement.</p>
<p>It feels too damn natural.</p>
<p>"A wish, huh. Now you remember it," funny but Moran knows that with that old debt Moriarty won't really play games. If he physically can, he'd fulfill any wish. That was their deal anyway.</p>
<p>And actually, right how he could say something like 'leave me alone and never appear again', or 'let me stay by your side as I did before', or just simply whatever.</p>
<p>Moran says nothing too busy to keep his calm facade when he feels that warm soft breath on his face.</p>
<p>"You came just because of the wish? Fine, here it is: stay alive. Now you owe me nothing," Sebastian's voice may sound cold and dry, but he knows he can't deceive JM being so close.</p>
<p>Because it's not an attempt to bid farewell. It's more like a disguised 'I want you to come to me not because of debt but because you really want to '. It's more like a desperate wish to start all over again, hidden under cold layers of harsh words.</p>
<p>JM was always too sharp-witted. The chance he wouldn't see it deep to the bottom of the heart is insignificantly tiny.</p>
<p>Rain is quite heavy and cold but right now Moran feels himself even a bit hot, not able to ignore their closeness and the touches he feels. Moriarty always loved to break him, and goddammit he was always successful in that.</p>
<p>Seems like this time, be it right now or later, he'd success again. But Moran knows he'd never give up without a silent fight, no matter if it's doomed since the first moment.</p>`
};

pagesData[34] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>"You really don't need anything from me, do you?" JM says after some silence. "Stay alive... I think I can do that." Then more teasing, which sounds strangely relieved, comes in a sigh: "What a boring wish..."</p>
<p>Those two years must have done dirty to JM's memory, making him forget that of all people, of all his partnerships that worked either because of intimidation or profit Sebastian Moran was the one who didn't need anything except being by his side. Maybe this simple request to stay alive is the vow he's been trying to get; the proof that Moran would remain loyal no matter what, but simply because it's in his nature.</p> 
<p>To protect JM, to take care of him – it's in Moran's nature.</p> 
<p>Seems like his plan, overly complicated and dramatic, turned out to be unnecessary after all, because everything could be achieved with "I want you to be mine again, please." Maybe JM just needed to wrap everything in layers of bullshit because he forgot how to be vulnerable, and Sebastian managed to outplay him this easily by refusing to play.</p>
<p>JM doesn't know what he's doing when he presses his lips to the corner of Sebastian's mouth, the one that was hurt, and starts pecking it with tiniest kisses, having a hard time trying not to miss because he's already shivering terribly. Now he's snuggling against him with desperation because the warmth of Sebastian's body feels so good, and the alternative for detaching from it would be curling up on the tombstone and try to keep warm against the thick cover of wet moss.</p>
<p>"Let's go home," JM mumbles through his clenched teeth. "Can I stay over?"</p>`
};

pagesData[35] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>It might be a really boring wish. Yet never should it be entertaining, since it's a sincere wish— from Moriarty's point of view, Moran is really quite boring. But isn't that what he appreciated? Something different, something that can balance and hold him, something he can always rely on. Even fucking now.</p>
<p>He doesn't shudder when feels a strangely soft and light kisses, almost innocent and a bit awkward actually; but it takes so much to stay composed.</p>
<p>Moran lets himself a weakness: he closes his eyes, exhaling bit sharply, and that small reaction shows just fucking everything.</p>
<p>He was always the one by JM's side who stayed just because he wanted. Moran wasn't a victim of blackmail or delicate manipulation, but he was a victim of his own bloody feelings. Emotions he couldn't control.</p>
<p>Maybe Moriarty still remembers it too well.</p>
<p>"Yes," Sebastian says, losing his voice then for a few very long seconds. "Sure. You can."</p>
<p>A fucking white flag he lays down to JM's feet. A fucking evidence of his total weakness. He finally frees JM's hand just to caress his wrist shorty and tender; then he's ready to step back but he doesn't, just saying, "You'll catch a cold, by the way."</p>
<p>Sebastian lets JM stay same close, catching some warmth.</p>
<p>And then they leave the cemetery, surely not hand in hand but still too fucking close. They stay too close all the way back: in a cab, getting up by stairs.</p>
<p>When they finally reach the flat, both are quite wet. "Take it off," Moran says nodding at JM's jacket. "I'll get something to drink."</p>
<p>That little standard care gives him a chance to pull himself together for a little bit more, but well— they both know that it will be really soon when emotions take over.</p>`
};

pagesData[36] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>On the way home JM is unusually quiet, staying close to Sebastian the whole time. The cab driver casts suspicious glances at them, probably thinking they're a couple of fags, but they couldn't care less.</p>
<p>He knows Moran's place too well though it's been a while since he last got to be a legitimate guest here. He remains at the door as Moran walks deeper into the room to get drinks. Outside the balcony window it's raining like crazy.</p>
<p>JM drops his wet jacket on the floor, because it's probably ruined anyway. He decides he could use a warm bath, and when Moran returns to look for him, he finds Moriarty already half-naked in the bathtub which is slowly filling up with steaming water; his position, arms criss-crossed on his chest, reminds the one of a dead man lying in a casket.</p>
<p>There's always been a certain beef between JM and the weather, with him believing he's too fucking special to be touched by such ordinary things like rain and cold, and the weather always proving him wrong, obviously. Another thing he liked about Sebastian – he never pitied him even at times like this.</p>
<p>So when Sebastian returns with their drinks, he demands him to leave them on the edge of the sink and get in, too.</p>
<p>The water level rises higher and higher, and the parts of the skin not yet submerged are getting covered with goosebumps from anticipation until water consumes them too.</p>
<p>The bathtub appears to be too big for JM, making it hard to keep his head above the water. Sebastian could easily drown him if he wanted, but it's probably better for JM not to think about it, because otherwise his excitement about this fantasy would grow too obvious.</p>`
};

pagesData[37] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>Two years passed yet it feels like nothing has changed. There's a nice big tub in Moran's flat, and occasionally JM would come and simply use it without asking. Maybe because he simply knew he'll never get a no.</p>
<p>So Moran isn't surprised at all. He has two simple porcelain mugs, filled with a hot mix of good whisky, apple juice and honey, a simple thing to get warm from the inside. And when he carefully places cups on the edge of the tub, he thinks it's probably a very good idea to take a warm bath after that cold shower. Even he himself, being so used to very different bad weather feels like too cold, no matter what flames are consuming from the inside.</p>
<p>Though the idea to get into the same tub right now doesn't feel like a good one.</p>
<p>"Relax and get warm," he says taking off his shirt which is kinda wet too, and taking a towel to dry his skin. "I'm fine enough."</p>
<p>For just a second, Moran thinks that it would take a minute maybe to drown JM so easily. And it actually won't be a real problem to dispose of the body.</p>
