pagesData[57] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>It’s rather double-facedly of Moran to be so nice and quiet now after the way he met JM face to face. But well, this duality was always one of his integral parts. Some would blame war that made him too aggressive and quick-tempered sometimes, some would say he was always a kind of bastard who does simply whatever. He wouldn’t try to find excuses because it’s just—well, normal. Especially at JM’s side.</p>
<p>So right now this quiet submissiveness is mixing with a stubborn yet calm obstinacy, when Sebastian looks into the dark eyes in front of him. He doesn’t try to read emotions or whatever, knowing too well what a good actor JM is, but he does what he can do the best: he patiently _waits_. Such silence sometimes gives much more effect that any words, be it plea, question or demand, or maybe threat.
<p>And after some silence, Moriarty speaks. His speech is bit slower than usual, as if he’s picking every word so very careful right now… or rather, if he’s not completely sure. That’s strange.</p>
<p>Moran doesn’t frown, his face doesn’t change at all, only the look in his eyes becomes collected and cold, but who would notice when it’s quiet dark around?</p>
<p>"You know I believe you," he says. "And you know I’m asking not out of vain curiosity."
Then there’s some silence again, and they both don’t move. Moran listens to JM’s breathing, to his heartbeat, feels his warmth. Fuck. He could just strangle him right now and finish all that sick bullshit.</p>
<p>Usually it would be JM speaking first, not able to be silent for long. But right now it’s Moran who licks his dry lips and says calmly, "You know that I need to know it. To make sure things would go right. I’m responsible for your safety, remember? And I don’t care if you’re sure or not. I really don’t care unless you’d just tell me whatever happened. Even if it happened only in your head."</p>
<p>It’s actually the moment he admits his agreement to come back, straightforwardly and open, but Moran couldn’t care less.
<p>He’s anyway always got the option of strangling.</p>`
};

pagesData[58] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>So, Sebastian's silence has always been very convincing, and he knows exactly how to weaponize it against JM's intolerance of an idea of someone being immune to his manipulations. It's probably what made him more involved into their specific relationship in the first place – playing Sebastian was hard, and the transition from the chased one into the chaser feels humiliating. No one gets to Jim Moriarty, whereas Jim Moriarty can get to anyone pretty easily. The experienced and uncompromising Sebastian Moran proves he's not just "anyone".</p>
<p>Another issue lies with honesty, truth, and whether to entrust important information that, in the wrong hands, can be used against you and your masterplan. It's in JM's habit to feed all sorts of nonsense to people around him until he actually needs them to know a teensie bit of his perspective in order to carry out a task. So Sebastian's words prove convincing here as well, since he really never asks anything out of vain curiosity. And it's another thing that allowed them to form such a long-term partnership – Moran never asked JM something he didn't want to tell.</p>
<p>Until now. And it's ridiculous how they both are so stubborn while lying in the same bed, dick to dick.</p>
<p>"So, obviously, I had to stay low for some time... For quite the time, actually..."</p>
<p>Something stops him from rushing straight into the story; probably, because his whole Reichenbach idea was so disgustingly flawed and messy, the usually perfect calculation unable to make up for its core hysterical obsessiveness. While cornering Sherlock two years ago, he knew he might need a backup plan and still made the main bet on going for an aggressive victory, a straight-forward checkmate which Sherlock managed to repel, leaving no other choice than to exchange a death for a death. Despite Moriarty having prepared his retreat in case of failure, he almost made his own death real by placing two types of bullets into the pistol: the blank ones that would stun him, and the loaded ones that would kill him – a whole game of Russian Roulette just because he couldn't decide. Lying on the roof, he wasn't sure which one actually hit him. To this day, he still wasn't sure.</p>
<p>In either case, he needed some medical assistance after escaping the roof, because the shock wave damaged his head and gave him a bad concussion. The hardest part was to keep acting according to plan and flee the city while reality was mixing with memory, and memory was mixing with fantasy.</p>
<p>He didn't expect to find himself so completely out of order, dysfunctional, almost lobotomized. Maybe it wasn't the brain injury, but the crushing weight of disappointment that stole a whole year from his life – the worst fucking year of hiding in his hometown and living not as Jim Moriarty, but as some ordinary, boring and worthless Jim.</p>
<p>Did Jim Moriarty even exist?</p>
<p>Too easy to believe into his own trick about JM being some fictional villain, the staged "Sherlock's nemesis". He could choose to keep it that way and never return. But when he got well enough to go out and walk around the places of his childhood, they awakened the memories of how it all started. And then the itch was back. The restlessness. Slowly he was becoming his old self again, the one who was thriving for puzzle, excitement, greatness and the twisted art of orchestrating things the way nobody else could – the criminal way.</p>
<p>He also missed Sebastian... A little... A lot... Well, the whole concept of "missing someone" is a little bit different from how JM is wired, but the man definitely occupied his mind a lot of the time, the desire to see and touch him again.</p>
<p>But JM doesn't confess this. Instead he lets the fatigue flow through his body and relax his muscles, places his head back on Moran's chest and blabbers about how he spent a year in his hometown, and how certain things never changed there, and how it was so boring that he cracked more than 1000 sudokus, and how he saw a lad who used to pick on him in high school…</p>
<p>"...and then I followed him to that miserable store he appears to run now, and then I started feeding the crows every time I passed by. And they occupied his place completely. Dozens, their crap everywhere! He's cooked. He's never gonna get rid of them. Say hello to bankruptcy!"</p>
<p>His blabbering becomes less and less coherent as he's slowly falling asleep, and just before giving in he mumbles that he has something "fun" planned for tomorrow, something both of them are going to take part in.</p>`
};

pagesData[59] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>Not that Moran really believes he’d hear the truth. Really. But he’s sharp-sighted enough so any words or even silence it always just a part of the answer itself for him. He listens not to words only, but to intonations, to tiny and almost invisible pauses, he notices the exact wording, analyzing it every time quickly; he takes into account the breathing, the moves, the mimics, the body tension. Simply said, everything. Being such observant is actually professional for him, so no wonder he couldn’t be taken over easily. With JM, he mastered this specific talent up to the bone. It was rather difficult first year of working with him, but then, upon their strange and slowly at first closing-in, he became much more experienced.</p>
<p>So right now he notes the long pause. The unusual manner of speech when JM starts to talk again, as if he’s not sure. This weird uncertainity isn’t about the trust issues or any other kind of games, absolutely not. Sebastian finds it hard to determine what it really is, but at least he knows what it isn’t.</p>
<p>And he can feel JM can’t answer because there is no answer in his brilliant head.</p>
<p>All this fucking story with fucking Sherlock Holmes was a grand failure since the very beginning, yet Moran couldn’t explain it—he just felt it, but what’s a weird intuition versus a stubborn genius? So all he had to do is just to follow as usual. He knew it won’t finish well. That obsession with the consulting detective was making Moriarty almost blind at some points, so he acted more and more impulsively, cheating on his usual cold-blooded premeditation manner.</p>
<p>And that’s how it finished, when Moran was actually completely right since the very beginning.</p>
<p>And here they are right now.</p>
<p>JM somehow still alive and acting strangely. Moran himself still alive for some reasons and not knowing what to do, to kill him or to come back by his side.</p>
<p>And Moriarty’s voice has an echo of something bitter in it, like he has been looking for something and never found.</p>
<p>There’s something more behind this mere words of silly stories. Something JM can’t maybe admit—or maybe, something he’s afraid to admit. That needs a bit more time to analyze and understand.</p>
<p>"Good night, James," Moran sighs under his breath when JM’s breathing changes to more even, typical for sleeping. So, ‘fun’. Knowing him, there would be nothing funny but definetely something dangerous—oh well, nothing new. Welcome back, one can say.</p>
<p>Moran finds himself smiling slightly when he thinks that sometimes JM’s crazy ideas and plans, absolutely dangerous and quite risky, were looking real fun for himself. He liked to take part in some of his intricate plays, so maybe… why not trying at least once more to check if it’s still same fun?</p>
<p>Moran still got the options. Or at least he wants to believe it.</p>
<p>Hours ago, in the morning, he’s in the kitchen, sipping strong black tea with milk and checking the newsfeed as usual, a habit he kept after JM’s death. He used to keep the track of events all the time, so he continued to do so for two more years. It’s quite easy with all this internet stuff, especially when you know a place or two to learn the real truth, since Moran perfectly know how easy it is to play tricks with information—oh, he witnessed it too often, sometimes taking part in it.</p>
<p>He hears some soft rustling in the bedroom and some quiet sounds of a man waking up, so he grabs his mug and goes to check. Cold, calm and composed as usual, wearing only comfy lounge pants since it’s rather warm in his flat today. Daylight exposes his body as is: sinewy, still bit tanned, with a few scars over his skin, an old tattoo he made in his student era, and a new ugly scar right under the ribs. Well, Moran could be dead by now, yet year ago he was lucky enough to block the deathblow of a big knife so it didn’t pierce his heart or lungs. It cost almost a month in a hospital, but well—not a big price to stay alive.</p>
<p>"Morning," he says almost dryly, watching every JM’s move carefully so to quickly understand what mask he’d put on right now.</p>`
};

pagesData[60] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>This night happened to be one of the most restful over the past month for JM, him gaining consciousness only once just to realize there's no danger and fall back asleep, clinging to Moran as if to make sure he wouldn't secretly escape; so in the morning JM takes a minute to wonder, how the man managed to get up without waking him, and the next thing he sees is Moran standing in the doorway with a mug, topless, staring down at him with a studying gaze.</p>
<p>"Ughhh... The early bird you are..." JM mumbles, rubbing the pillowmarks off his face.</p>
<p>It's never easy when memory returns to your newborn mind in the morning, flooding it intrusively with thoughts about your affairs: things that need to be done, decisions to be made, and the ones you have made in the past, still revising your mistakes over and over, all the burden dragging after you from yesterday; just things you wish to stay distracted from, the inability of this world to fully satisfy your needs and appeal to your drives.</p>
<p>Usually JM would spend some time sitting in bed, his head in his hands, as if trying to fit the impossible restlessness of his cognition into the limited capacity of human flesh.</p>
<p>He gulps from the glass of water Sebastian prepared yesterday because his lips feel dry. He remembers that, probably, in his dream he saw Sherlock hiding behind 1-9 number sequences, the sudoku grids transforming into the markings of a swimming pool, and a flock of crows pecking at a human brain through an open skull. He remembers the story he told Moran before falling asleep and kinda regrets that it was so improvised and unconvincing.</p>
<p>He remembers he's still naked under the covers and Moran is standing right there, staring silently.</p>
<p>It feels disarming to be perceived with such intensity before being able to put on any mask at all. Again, Moran is the only person who ever had a chance to see him like this, because JM never felt safe enough to sleep by anybody else's side. Even the British Government couldn't take him by surprise during a full-time supervision in the dungeon.</p>
<p>The bathrobe is still hanging over a chair but it's out of reach, unfortunately. JM stares back at Moran and realises he's not gonna give him a moment of privacy to dress, so fuck it, there's nothing new in acting overconfident and exhibitionistic. So he rises and walks across the room to pick up the bathrobe, then fixes his hair and approaches Sebastian cockily.</p>
<p>"Well hello there," he meets Sebastian in the doorway, paying attention to his body, eyeing the old tattoo he always deemed pretty erotic, and the new scar he noticed earlier but didn't try to ask about. "You look very... awaken. Couldn't wait for the new day?"</p>
<p>He passes to the kitchen whistling a silly melody that's stuck in his head, then turns the TV on, destroying the peaceful silence of Sebastian's apartment. The newschannel is buzzing with reports on the digital heist, blaming it on politically motivated organizations and being absurd in its inaccuracy. JM giggles. The television is such a ridiculous medium, but no television nor the print or even the internet knows the truth. The ex security officer commits suicide, there've been several traffic accidents over the city last night, the weather is going to get better after the storm, a new single released by a popular musician, top tier companies are working on new construction projects, etc, etc.</p>
<p>JM looks around in search of his clothes he left there somewhere yesterday, thinking he gotta take it to the laundry, or get a new suit for today's arrangements. Luckily, despite him not rushing to wake up, they have plenty of time to have breakfast and then make a stop at his favorite atelier.</p>
<p>Still holding the remote, he pokes it teasingly into Moran's abs just where the scar is, not realizing it might trigger his instinct of blocking a knife-sized object being pressed between his ribs; or maybe he's doing it intentionally. "So, care to tell me where this came from?"</p>
<p>A year ago, JM heard from his spies that Moran spent a month in a hospital, and he even bribed some nurses for information or special assistance in case of emergency, but luckily there was none. So now he's just curious, or rather wants to have another good look on Moran in the daylight.</p>`
};

pagesData[61] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>The early bird he is, and Moran simply watches JM slowly waking up. Just like it always has been; and are those years ‘always’? It doesn’t matter, actually. Such moments were always quite interesting, to see Moriarty before he chooses a mask or a role for today, or at least for next hour. Almost like to see a human behind the grotesque image of the evil genius. Not for a long time anyway, because JM quickly composes himself, getting up and throwing on the bathrobe.</p>
<p>Moran doesn’t mention that there’s an ‘emergency suit’ still in his wardrobe, left there three years ago by JM after one accident when he hadn’t anything to change. He wonders if Moriarty remembers that, since his clothes are still partly wet—yesterday Moran wasn’t in condition to make anything about them.</p>
<p>No questions about clothes follow, so Moran quickly makes the bed reflexively, then listens for the sound of TV turned on in the kitchen. Last time he turned it on was few months ago just to watch some football game of the World Cup. Now it’s news, and well, it’s still same mildly annoying.</p>
<p>Sebastian walks to the kitchen to wash his mug and maybe make some breakfast, though he often misses it; the image of JM sitting there as if nothing happened is quite dazzling. As he passes by, there’s some short movement, and Moran reacts mindlessly, to realize a moment later that this is just the remote, nothing dangerous. He lets go JM’s wrist which he grabbed neatly and quickly, and answers, "From a knife. Zero out of ten, not recommending".</p>
<p>He feels an intense gaze on his back while walking to the sink and quickly washing the mug, then drying his hands with a towel. A silent question, because JM hates when he plays with his curiosity like this.</p>
<p>So Moran turns to face him, as if still thinking if he shall answer, and then says dryly, "One of your old friends decided it would be nice to play tricks on me. He could succeed though. So are you going to tell about your ‘fun’ for today?"</p>
<p>He asks the question in the same calm voice, not changing intonations at all, making no pause. Usual manner, since this way he got answers from JM much more often. And it’s even funny how that simple trick worked with that brilliant mind.</p>`
};

pagesData[62] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>JM brews the tea for himself and drinks it slowly, bending low over the table and flexing his wrist that survived yet another grabbing. He eyes Moran over the edge of the mug and observes his movement across the kitchen, which is equipped with different kinds of fancy appliances, chrome-surfaced. A very nice view certainly, the man keeping himself occupied and useful, even though his guest could help himself and wouldn't demand anything at least verbally (set aside the little sabotaging chaos of abandoned clothes and undone sheets). Sometimes JM wonders if economy is just a method invented by Sebastian to avoid his intensity, the intrusive attention of his eyes; but he can, and will, confront them if needed, as he does it now.</p>
<p>By the way, the back is a highly underestimated part of the body.</p>
<p>So it's a deal then, a fair exchange of information; to learn more, tell more. He decides to sell the details of his plan for Sebastian's replies, one at a time.</p>
<p>"One of MY old friends, and you're telling me only now? If he chose to prove his point like this, then he shouldn't be walking the earth."</p>
<p>He circles his fingers over the remote buttons absent-mindedly, then turns down the sound of television a bit.</p>
<p>"We're invited to a party! A very official one. And you're gonna need your military uniform because those pretty medals sparkling on your chest will help me sneak wherever I want. *Excuse me sir, guests are not allowed in this area‐ Oh dang it, I am so sorry Colonel! Surely, you can pass. What? This unbelievably handsome and immaculately dressed gentleman is with you? I guess your companion can pass too. Yes sir, thank you sir*." He impersonates an imaginary guard, mimicking a salute, then breaks laughing. "No public speeches on your behalf, I promise. We're just gonna listen and watch. My turn with the question. By any chance, do you know who it was exactly, that knifeplay enthusiast?"</p>`
};

pagesData[63] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>Household routine is greatly underestimated, if you ask. It was even before meeting JM when Moran discovered that simple things like cooking, cleaning, and so on help to ground the mind, as if it’s some cleaning for inquietudes too. So right now he snerks and inspects his fridge to make a couple of sandwiches just to make his hands busy.</p>
<p>Grim Reaper on his tattoo, performed quite skillful, has an effect of a picture watching directly the observer no matter where they are. So either Sebastian watches JM or the dark image from his upper arm; and that’s a bit absurd.</p>
<p>A very official party. Crap, Moran hates it when he doesn’t know the details, and JM loves not telling it, so here they are again. And the old game of exchanging answers, but at least—they do play it. Better than nothing.</p>
<p>So he listens, not showing any reaction, then takes a sit in front of Moriarty, placing a cutting board with a couple of sandwiches between them, and keeps silence for few more seconds before asking. Perfectly composed again, he doesn’t let emotions slip through his usual coldness, but gosh, it’s so fucking stupid after what happened yesterday night.
Still again, nothing new, because seems like this stubborn dance of never admitting the truth is endless.</p>
<p>"Why, I do," he says, shrugging slightly. Another one pause just to annoy JM. "The infamous Mr. Malcolm McColey, or as he preferred, Mr. M Doe, may he rest in peace. Or may not, actually. I took him out couple of months later, you know I really hate hospitals. So whose party is that?"</p>
<p>And same again, no pauses, no voice change, no emotions—perfect good old very English etiquette. Moran knows how to play this game, though it’s hard while being in the gun sight of black devil’s eyes.</p>
<p>For sure, he doesn’t trust JM now.</p>
<p>Though did he ever really trust? Or maybe it’s another one self deceit, and he did all the time? It’s difficult to say, but Moran keeps thinking he just doesn’t trust, never had and never will.</p>
<p>It’s actually also kinda absurd since there were many times when he turned his back to JM, entrusting him own life, in so many different situations.</p>
<p>But well, JM never was false to that. Or was he? Hell knows if Sebastian is still alive and maybe even back on track.</p>`
};

pagesData[64] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>JM seems relaxed, but the silences are becoming awkward. He fights down a yawn and starts munching on the sandwich, trying to look patient and nonchalant, then the answer spills, and maybe his reaction is just a little bit too theatrical.</p>
<p>"The DOE?! The Malcolm "Why Won't My Nickname Stick Dammit" McColey? I suppose we should call him John Doe from now on. That pain in the ass... I guess, in the end he had something personal against you, didn't he? Huh..."</p>
<p>He keeps munching, eyes squinted, as if sinking into his memories for a moment – or trying to imagine how Sebastian did it: the classic way, or pushed him down the stairs, perhaps, or poisoned his dishware; because it would be a mistake to think of Moran only as a sniper and not an experienced assassin. But there's a rule – once the job's done, you shouldn't be too nosy about it, you should never pose a compromising question. It's a good thing he's gone.</p>
<p>So whose party is that? Instead of answering, JM turns up the volume on the TV, and the female correspondent speaks for him:</p>
<p>"The grand opening of the London Port will be celebrated today — a project that has been in construction for almost 20 years, previously suspended because the completed sections needed to be put into operation ahead of schedule due to its crucial role in transporting military cargo to Iraq. But today the key lead developer is proudly announcing the port's complete serviceability for civilian use, expressing their gratitude to the Ministry of Defence for cooperation. All sponsors who participated in this challenging project are invited to today's event. Stay tuned for the reportage..."</p>
<p>JM presses the 'off' button, and it goes quiet.</p>
<p>"Lots of money stolen over there," he comments. "Many contractors gone bankrupt. All so that those crooks could boast today. To me, this waterfront used to be valuable, but not anymore since it's being handed to the city council. You'll see." He gives him another mysterious look.</p>`
};

pagesData[65] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>Did the deceased have something personal against Moran? Hell knows. Maybe just wanted to be sure there won’t be any more menace even after JM’s death; or maybe that was because Moran rejected his proposal casually. That guy wasn’t much fun, so who cares when he’s six feet down now.</p>
<p>Moriarty makes TV louder, and Moran turns his head a little bit, so to keep an eye on him but pay some attention to news at the same time while eating his sandwich. London Port, really? That shithole of milking? Sounds kind of crazy, but oh, that’s JM. One should worry when he makes something so-called normal. Though anyway, what can be done there—Sebastian got no idea of that.</p>
<p>"You know that to make things work you have to cough up some useful stuff?" He’s not like asking, this sounds more like a statement.</p>
<p>Then he gets up as if to clean up the table, grabs the cutting board and makes a step aside to place it. A moment later, he’s already behind Moriarty’s back, with a usual chef knife in his hand dangerously close to the neck. And no doubts it’s sharp: Moran keeps all his the things at home in perfect condition.</p>
<p>"You better remember I’m not one of your expendables… and oh, you must have forgot that nice little note in my dossier, did you? I’m still not sure if I like your comeback," Moran whispers, feeling the urge to break something right now.</p>
<p>That ‘nice little note’ told everyone he has some anger issues. Or rather, serious issues. A fake note actually; Moran made it up so to have an extra ace up his sleeve. Though there _are_ some issues, and Moriarty knows that well. The question is, did it change last two years? Maybe got worse? Maybe weakened?</p>
<p>Or maybe Sebastian does it because he knows JM likes to feel that threat sometimes, he likes to see how gracefully Moran deals with any knife? From that point of view, this cold menace could actually be a part of very specific flirting between two of them. Like a youngster trying to impress a high school girl he likes.</p>`
};

pagesData[66] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>It appears like JM didn't expect to get this reaction because when he eyes the large knife hanging inches from his neck and then lifts his face to look up at Moran, he seems genuinely surprised. With his head tilted back, his throat becomes even more exposed to the blade. The thing with JM is – as long as you're watching, you'll always get an emotional reaction, even if ninety percent of it is just him clowning around, mocking what he believes a human emotion is supposed to look like.</p>
<p>Right now he's staring up at Moran in disbelief.</p>
<p>"What now, you're gonna make me cry for help and piss myself?" he murmurs in a high pitch, smiling mischievously, as if trying to offend Sebastian with not taking him seriously enough. "We both know that 'nice little note' in your dossier is a bluff. Ain't it, tough guy? Otherwise I'll need to call the police and report a domestic violence!.."</p>
<p>What he's doing is taking on the role of an overly arrogant high school bitch who can be humbled only by forcing a dick up her pussy, which, at this point, is asking for it with this excessive audacity; maybe then she's gonna be fucking impressed.</p>
<p>Is this still a roleplay though? Because with pushing too hard, there's still a danger of being hurt for real, and the sharpness of the knife is very real too. JM tries it with his finger and flinches immediately as if he did not expect it to cut this easily, and then it seems like the late realization of being threatened washes the cheekiness off his face, as he looks at Moran again, blinking, his lips slightly pursed with what seems to be fear, or at least a very convincing imitation of it. Playing the victim is a kinky bait.</p>`
};

pagesData[67] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>"A bluff, you say? Oh, you can never be sure with a vet, you know," Moran almost whispers, his voice low, calm and giving an uncomfortable impression of lethal danger. "Time has passed, you know. As well as we both know that maybe the note is a bluff, but there are some things noone wrote there." His last words are told so closely that his breathing touches JM’s cheekbone.</p>
<p>Then Moran straightens up, looking at a knife in his hand like it’s some kind of innocent toy and not a sharp blade dangerously close to the exposed neck.</p>
<p>"You better behave," he says, "otherwise I won’t. I’m fed to the teeth with your silence."
For sure he won’t explain what he means exactly. It might sound like he just hates when he has to do something not seeing at least half of the picture; or maybe he speaks about last two years? It’s only upon Moriarty to decide.</p>
<p>Then the knife turns blunt side to be softly pressed to the neck first, then sliding up to the cheek before Moran finally removes it. Yet he’s still behing the back, trying extremely hard to kill the urge to rummage his fingers through JM’s hair.</p>
<p>He almost fails.</p>
<p>It’s a sick and wicked game they play, when Moran whispers to be careful with dangerous things, and hells knows if he means the knife, himself, or big games JM loves to play here and there.</p>
<p>And right now Sebastian looks like a predator captured his prey, but noone can be sure who’s a real predator, a real danger here. Still, although that whole scene was maybe just a senseless show-off, it was over two years ago he used to do like that sometimes. To recall JM who’s at his side; but more—because JM really liked such show-offs back then, favoring it with his kinky attention and weird affection.</p>`
};

pagesData[68] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>If it was Sebastian to stab McColey in a dark alley and not the other way around, there'd be no way he would miss, because JM's man is so much more advanced in knifeplay. They used to practise it so often after all, like now, when the blade knows exactly the right artery to press at.</p>
<p>If you want to take somebody out, you've only got one try or you shouldn't try at all. You fail – you're dead. And with Sebastain Moran – it's a fucking guarantee. It makes Moriarty feel proud.</p>
<p>During Moran's speech, he doesn't break eye-contact, like a good student who's doing his best to listen to the teacher explaining the ABC's, something important and basic, something worth the calm preaching in a quiet classroom; he doesn't blink, though his eyelids tremble, and both of his hands slowly slide under the table and between his thighs.</p>
<p>When the blunt side of the knife is pressed against his throat, he struggles to swallow though it's hard to do with head tilted back. And when it's on his face, he closes his eyes and turns slightly towards the cool metal to rub his cheek alongside it, despite the bad friction quality between its surface and skin.</p>
<p>And just when he intends to kiss the knife, take it between his lips maybe, it's gone; because Moran doesn't want JM to play with dangerous stuff.</p>
<p>However, speaking of dangerous stuff, it's too late. Because he has already developed a habit of playing with Sebastian, and with other flammable materials too.</p>
<p>"I'm literally gonna be so, so well-behaved," he hums, squinting at Sebastian cunningly with one eye, while fighting the desire to start stroking himself under the robe. Why shouldn't he do this though?</p>
<p>"I thought you loved silence!.. You'd like to know what I want?" he pauses as if warming Sebastian up for another dirty talk. "With the port. I want to blow this tedious place to the ground. We'll watch the fireworks... The whole country will watch... By the way, what do you think about getting there a little bit early and have a look around? It's good memories, after all. Come on and get dressed, it's been a while since I last saw you in your uniform. Hope it still fits."</p>`
};

pagesData[69] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>Being usually a silent menacing shadow behind JM’s shoulder, Moran is really used to note and rememer all the small details, and he does it with JM himself too. Like right now, when he watches the reaction to the knife, the obvious slight tension, bit uneven breathing, closed eyes, and some kind of maybe unconscious intention to lean closer to the cold metal. So Sebastian likes what he sees, though maybe he shouldn’t. Satisfied with that reaction, he steps back, placing the knife neatly in the holder.</p>
<p>For sure, JM would never be ‘well-behaved’. Just not his nature at all, no matter what kind of sense you put into that words. But well, that was one of the reasons Moran started to work with him, and it’s exactly the ‘with’, not ‘for’. ‘For’ stage was just about money and some issues Moran had after his retirement, since the retirement wasn't voluntary.</p>
<p>Moran crosses his arms, listening calmly, then gives a very short smirk. "Fireworks, then. Fine." He gives JM one more long, contemplative look, then simply says, "You better get out of that robe as well. Your stuff is in the same place as usual."</p>
<p>And then he walks out of the kitchen, first to check his laptop left in the living room for any notifications. So, now he sees at least a part of the big picture: the Port, the fire. It could mean nothing, but Moran remembers the ideas from three, four years ago, since JM had some different plans about that place. Knowing those plans and knowing Moriarty’s style, it’s not so very difficult for him to build a bigger picture.</p>
<p>And the good old, almost forgotten thrill flares up inside, so maybe it would be good idea to put the strangling option aside for a while and check for the ‘party’ first.</p
<p>Moran tries not to think how often he was following that wicked path: wanting to get rid of JM, but then waiting again because some fun shall happen; and day by day, month by month it grew into something new, coming to a point where getting rid was never an option.
Crap, same old trap again, and he walks into in by his free will and even with enthusiasm.</p>
<p>And his ceremonial full dress is in perfect condition, both No.1 and No.2, yet he chooses the second one since the even isn’t so very high-class. Not like it’s a dinner with Her Majesty, after all; and Moran still looks great in both. He can actually look great in field camouflage, since it’s not the dress that gives a man that high-ranking officer vibe, it’s something inside.
Plus, no matter what happened in the head and in the emotions all that time, Moran still used to keep himself perfectly fit, his body ready for any kind of load, his appearance neat and worthy of a gentleman.</p>
<p>"I still need details," he says, adjusting his tie, "safety issues. You know what I think of fireworks."</p>
<p>It can be even a bit funny, since JM loves to put things on fire, and Moran was a Royal Engineer for a long time, mainly working exactly with all the explosive stuff. Kind of perfect match, though some people would rather call it a pure disaster.</p>`
};

pagesData[70] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>If you need to find the biggest shithole for money laundering, the ultimate provider of fake job positions, inconspicuous storage boxes, just rooms to dip people into tanks of acid and then dump their bodies into the river – you should aim for construction sites or waterfronts, or a port in construction, or a port that's been in construction for so long that it's become an unsupervised mess. With its unclear financial model and thousands of warehouses, containers, cranes and berths occupying almost 100 square miles, the Port has become the Grand Canyon of crime: nobody knew what was really happening there, and nobody was responsible since the constructor changed so often.</p>
<p>It has developed into an ecosystem, certain areas serving the military and therefore more risky to use, others rather abandoned and therefore more suitable for shady business. JM used to make profit from all of them though. Ships coming and going, provision and weaponry, much of it unlicensed – special orders delivered for Moriarty's clients from overseas. Many years ago, he found a way to establish his complete rule over this place, competing with other criminal authorities who were operating here and would fight like savages to keep by this feeder. But he managed to wipe them out, putting an end to probably what happened to be the most violent war in the world of organized crime for the past two decades. From that moment, everyone who wanted to use the Port for their operations needed to pay tax to Moriarty.</p>
<p>But, again, this was many years ago.</p>
<p>Today the Port is just a 100 mi² of hanging tails. Some of the locked boxes are probably still filled with shitpiles of evidence left by careless mobsters for the Scotland Yard. So JM contacted his old clients and offered to destroy their compromising material; or rather it was them who begged him to do that, ready to pay pretty much any price. So the show JM's orchestrating tonight will be watched by EVERYONE: his clients (obviously), the party attendants, the businessmen, the government, the Queen of England, the Scotland Yard, ordinary viewers sticking to their TV's...</p>
<p>...and, of course, Sherlock, who eventually will be asked to investigate this.</p>
<p>JM almost forgot he had left one of his suits in Moran's wardrobe. It's not his favorite but still a good one, an old Alexander McQueen collection – a double breasted two-piece, silky, in dusty pink- wait, PINK is NOT for a FORMAL wear, what the hell was he thinking? It probably ended up as a backup option just because he couldn't find a proper occasion to wear it. He puts it on and ponders for eternity whether he's going to stand out too much and whether he likes the color which is an unusual choice for him.</p>
<p>Then he meets Moran in the kitchen, and the contrast between them is pretty funny, but the man looks just as fuckable as JM remembers.</p>
<p>"Oh hi, soldier... You're alone here? Can I buy you a drink?" he approaches him playfully and, while messing with his tie, recalls one of their foreplay scripts that he suggested once, according to which Sebastian is a recent demob who hadn't got laid in months, and then they meet in a bar, and then... Well.</p>
<p>"...Crap, I can't go blowing up town-turning enterprises looking like a springtime flower. There're BOMBS Moran, dynamite, plenty all over the place. I mean, in certain areas, mostly – so no harm to people as long as they stay within the celebration hall. All that we gotta do is convince the counsel to press the sweet red button... I could press it myself but imagine the effect, plus his fingerprints on it, he'll fucking RUSH to Baker Street begging to restore his alibi."</p>
<p>JM pulls Sebastian's tie out of the collar, even though he just tucked it, and tugs slightly, which could imply an invitation for kissing or just be another flirty bait. Though JM seems unsure again. "I hope this won't trigger your PTSD... *I* wanna be your PTSD... ... I-I don't know, what do you think?" he asks finally, not clarifying if he means the suit, or the plan, or something else entirely (but most likely the suit). God, there was a time when he decided to try different colors aside from his favorite blue-gray-black palette and it turned out to be a catastrophe.</p>`
};

pagesData[71] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>Well. Moran knew there’s some JM’s suit in his wardrobe, but honestly, he wasn’t sure which exactly. Or rather, he didn’t care, just accepting the fact that there a suitcase, and there’s something in that suitcase, and that belongs to JM, and actually he had to throw it away two years ago.</p>
<p>But dammit, maybe it’s just some bats in belfry—but with some things Moran did completely nothing, as if it can change the history. Though on the other hand, Moriarty is actually back. So who knows.</p>
<p>So when he sees JM in that weird soft color, he raises an eyebrow just a tiny bit, being absolutely not sure that suits in that colour shall exist. Moran says nothing, letting Moriarty be a chatterbox again, so he could tell a bit more of his plans and ideas. And mention the bloody Baker Street, for fucking sure.</p>
<p>That obsession with Sherlock Holmes was a great idee fix, and Moran couldn’t be sure what he feels about it. Annoyance, some kind of jealousy, anxiety since it was dangerous enough? Hell knows.</p>
<p>Unlike his elder brother, that Sherlock was another one psycho, and maybe a psycho of a kind close to JM. So for sure one should be worry when two ticking bombs are getting closer to each other. Moran just slowly burned with a great dismay. And well, in the end it was what it was two years ago, so maybe all his negative forecasts turned to be real.</p>
<p>Nothing unpredictable that JM is still obsessed even now. Moran fights the reflex to grab JM’s hand when he reaches to the tie, showing no reaction at all, but hearing the uncertainity in his voice, just smirks.</p>
<p>So, a PTSD. For a moment, Moran wants to say, you are not a PTSD and never will be, ‘cos you’re much worse. Instead, he says, "I think you look a bit like an idiot. It’s absolutely not your color, so you must have been too drunk when chose that. And what about the Port, I suppose that shouldn’t be a big issue to make them play by your rules."</p>
<p>Making really, really bad things by proxy was always a good option, very JM’s style. And well, Moran usually approved it since it gave less risks and much more fun. Seeing somebody becoming a puppet under Moriarty’s subtle manipulations, that was like looking at a beautiful work of art exposed in some good old museum.</p>
<p>"The official ceremony starts in three and a half hours. Knowing the stuff, it’s more like four hours." Moran doesn’t continue his words, leaving it to JM to interpret what does he mean exactly. Maybe because there are few meanings, about the suit, the plan itself, the people and the security issued.</p>`
};

pagesData[72] = {
    author: "JM", // or "SM" depending on parity (even index = JM, odd = SM)
    text: `<p>"It's a limited collection! It probably costs a fortune now," JM exclaims with exaggerated resentment. "Plus it's supposed to be a disguise, so I shouldn't look completely like myself." He lingers for a minute to toy with the buttons on Moran's uniform, then his phone lights up and he examines it. "By the way, I need you to drive the car today... Don't want any third parties involved".</p>
<p>They actually have to walk a couple of blocks until they arrive to a multi-level parking, and among the rows of luxury cars find a black Porsche prepared for JM: it's most certainly stolen and has a fake tag. JM extracts the keys from a locker and throws them to Sebastian, the sound of them jingling in the air sending an echo through the floor.</p>
<p>Soon after departing JM asks to make a stop at the grocery store because he wants a gum and something to drink, even though they're probably overdressed to do the groceries. People stare weird at the two men looking picturesque together: the one in ceremonial military who's holding a perfectly straight posture while the other in a flamboyant suit is navigating between the shelves with soda.</p>
<p>The road takes an hour from the three and a half hours. This whole thing feels so casual, the way JM switches the music on the radio and sings along to Madonna and then dozes off with a can of Pepsi in his lap – makes it seem just like another one of their regular going outs.</p>
<p>Soon they pass the checkpoint and enter the territory; there are ships standing in the docks, tall cranes piercing into the thick fog, and thousands of colorful containers lining for miles and miles around. JM reaches into the backseat and finds the wire cutters. "Let's open some Christmas presents," he comments.</p>
<p>The area looks desolate, and most of the containers have weird markings on them, and they have to wander between the rows of rusty tanks for about ten minutes until JM spots the specific sign that indicates the one they're gonna open. This is not the first time he takes Sebastian to a little walk around the port, though even back then it used to be full of surprises, and things they stumble upon around every other corner keep getting worse: from needles, crowbars and other garbage to limbs of a stale dead body, which were carelessly left to rot in a barrel ("Ew," – JM).</p>
<p>Finally, there's the tall box still standing on a truck like it was abandoned right in the middle of transportation. Breaking the lock chain is not easy even though JM's far from weak physical-wise, so he asks Sebastian for assistance; and once the doors fly open, he climbs inside into what seems to be a storage room – more boxes filled with different stuff. Upon closer inspection – it's guns packed into vacuum bags: Glocks, Berettas, SIG Sauers etc.</p>
<p>"Treat yourself," JM says, while appearing more interested in the archive of some papers, hard drives and disposable motorola flip phones.</p>
<p>Everything is very old, though barely touched. There's also a drawer filled with fake identity cards, some of them recreating the ID's of British Army soldiers, looking weirdly familiar. Could Moran meet them before?</p>`
};

pagesData[73] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>Funny, but that ‘limited collection’ cheers up a little bit, since Moran still thinks JM looks a bit like idiot, and that’s actually funny. It’s refreshing, to feel that little clean hilarity, a feeling that shouldn’t belong here but it does. And he’s almost sure Moriarty knows about this silent laughter but does or says nothing, letting him have fun. Hell knows is it arrogance, condescension, or just a normal human behaviour.</p>
<p>So they walk out to the car, and it all feels just right, as it was just right years before. Moran catches the keys, quickly examines the unknown model, but the moment he starts the engine it seems like he had driven such car for an eternity. He’s a good driver, so sometimes he had to act as one when JM needed somebody experienced and reliable enough. Porsche smoothly dodges the heavy traffic, and when JM asks to stop at some Tesco, Moran doesn’t ask and just turns to the grocery.</p>
<p>They must be looking like they’ve run away from some event to refresh, since they’ve got soda, chewing gum, and a bottle of usual sparkling water Moran took just in case. But every moment somebody’s gaze becomes too intensive, Sebastian gives one in responce: in such way that a person prefers to get away as quick as possible.</p>
<p>Moran feels some relief when they reach their destination, because pop music could give him headache. But sadly, Moriarty didn’t appreciate early Pink Floyd or The Doors on the road, so he had to leave it for himself.</p>
<p>He drinks some water while they walk through the endless rows of containers, and finally feels himself fine enough. It’s cleaner here than before, but still most of containers look rusty and in poor condition, like this part is still forgotten. Or rather, everything was done to make this part be forgotten. Everyone needs a place for some fishy dealings.</p>
<p>While JM keeps looking for stuff he needs, Moran keeps an eye on surroundings, being ready to react any moment. Yet there’s noone around, even when they make some noise while breaking the chain which is surprisingly thick. JM alone can’t deal with it, so they have to work on it together, finally making the container open.</p>
<p>Still, before entering Sebastian waits for a while, listening to every sound around them. Still nothing, so he walks in, not turning his back to the doors, and takes a look at the stuff in boxes.</p>
<p>"It’s a squander," he answers quitely. "Stuff lies here long enough, and I can see even from here that all those poor kids are not in their best state."</p>
<p>Well, to ensure weapon is reliable, one shall keep it in a proper way. A vaccuum bag with no grease isn’t the best idea, honestly. Even though some guns look nice, noone can be sure they won’t misgive or jam at any moment.</p>
<p>So he switches his attention to papers which drawn JM’s attention. Some ID, and wait.</p>
<p>"Oh. The dead do really come back, what a weird apocalypse we got," he says dryly. "Alas, poor Yorick! I knew him, Horatio. We were sent to hell together with Captain McGregor. I was lucky enough though, he wasn’t."</p>
<p>Moreover, this trip to hell also let Captain Moran become Major Moran, but well, he deserved that. Though it’s even more interesting now why somebody would wake up the dead from so long ago. And Moran is sure he saw a few names he knows, so he tells it JM too while still keeping an eye on doors and listening to sounds outside.</p>
<p>And he hears some voices a minute later, so upon a quick thinking, he simply closes the doors — gently enough to make it almost silently, and leaving just a small crack between them. The chain is lying inside, so for a quick look nothing shall look suspicious. Now it’s really dark inside, but the voices come closer, talking about the today's big ceremony in a lazy and sarcastical way.</p>
<p>Moran feels himself a little bit like in some ancient tomb, alongside the evil spirit of it embodied in a man dressed in silly expensive suit.</p>`
};

pagesData[74] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>JM's attempts to try several motorolas, but the batteries are dead so it's no use; then he decides to save a copy of certain blanks with his phone camera. However, when Moran points out Captain McGregor and other names, he suddenly puts his papers aside and gently moves the box away from Sebastian's hands: "Erm, you're not supposed to see this. Sorry!"</p>
<p>But before any explanation can be required, they overhear two voices coming closer, chatting, and JM and Moran both freeze into state of alertness in the dark of carefully shut doors. The two porters appear to be on a quick inspection, or just taking a shortcut, passing through this section on a way towards the ceremonial hall; smoking.</p>
<p>"Aw shawks mate, this place sucks. I've already counted, like, five rats? And an otter, I think," one of them says, disgusted, as he kicks a crate and the flying garbage hits the metal wall of the container, sending a cacophony of noise over Moran and JM's heads like they're inside the Big Ben. "All this rush, and they wouldn't even care to tidy up before handing it to the city council. No more football for the kids, right?"</p>
<p>"Whaddya gonna do?" replies the older one.</p>
<p>JM quickly thinks of a plan in case the doors open, preparing to drop on his knees in front of Sebastian to make it look like they're just a couple of perverts who hid here for a quick blowjob – it'd be hilariously ridiculous and probably risky for the Colonel's reputation, but unlikely those fools would be able to identify his persona, and it'd allow to shoo the attention away from the contents of this storage. ...Ooor maybe two improvised corpses wouldn't hurt and they could get away with it. The wire cutters are still here somewhere, and they're heavy enough to promise a deadly contact with the crown of the head.</p>
<p>"What's in there anyway?"</p>
<p>"Why do you care? Just a lot of really old junk, I guess."</p>
<p>"BridgeInvest Shipping. Blackthorn Logistics. Thorpe Holdings. Crownford Construct." he reads the logos out loud. "Ever heard about any of these?"</p>
<p>"They all sound the same to me. Always a random combination of 'Invest', 'Logistics', 'Construct', or whatever. All likely liquidated now."</p>
<p>"No, the Blackthorne is doing fine, though. The Blackthorne Holdings? Didn't they incorporate the... ugh, the Something-Something Invest company? Shit, I forgot. I heard on today's news."</p>
<p>"The news, mate? Whatever, I don't care."</p>
<p>They start walking past the container and slow down, their figures visible through the thin gap, how they're stomping on cigarette butts for an unacceptably long time. Why can't those idiots just fucking MOVE IT? JM feels a strong desire to cover his mouth with his palm, just because he's so endlessly annoyed, though nothing would ever make him break the silence in a situation like this. The drunk soda starts to bubble in his belly, now from all moments, and this sound feels impossibly loud and embarrassing. He squints up at Moran and, in the single beam of daylight coming from outside, he can see his eyes fixed unwaveringly on the two potential targets: there's no doubt he'll get at their throats even before JM will have a chance to play any buffoonery.</p>
<p>"Ok. Are you staying for the lightshow?"</p>
<p>"No way. I'd rather grab a beer and watch a game."</p>
<p>"You don't wanna see the Lord Mayor press the mystery button and make the lasers align into the Union Jack in the sky?"</p>
<p>"Align into my ass. I press buttons every day, mate. You're up for a beer with me?"</p>
<p>"You know what? Hell yeah."</p>
<p>And they start walking away, to be completely gone in what feels like 4-5 minutes. After the silence proves itself, JM swallows down a nervous lump, realizing he's been tugging at Sebastian's clothes for the whole time.</p>
<p>"Imagine recieving a blowjob here," he giggles in the dark, and what seems to be a very random thing to say is actually an elaboration of his previous idea (he might as well consider doing this since they've got an hour+ before the ceremony, but it'd require to be completely out of one's mind to not realize Moran would twist his head off on the spot). "That smell though... A huge turn off. Remind me to return to it later!"</p>`
};

pagesData[75] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>Sometimes Moran behaved in a way which completely fulfilled his soldier name he used to have for last ten years of service. Tigers were cats anyway, and all cats were silent patient predators, capable of keeping attention on their victim no matter what. So it was same moment now, when he focused on the two bypassers, fixing every their step, listening to their conversation carefully.</p>
<p>If they dare to notice something’s wrong,— well, civcas happens. Not like those old rusty containers won’t hide two more poor bodies actually.</p>
<p>Still, in the back of his mind, Moran thinks about why JM was so worried that he saw these IDs. Was it a part of some other game? Was it something more? It happened quite often though when Sebastian learned much more that he should, be it by accident like now or intentionally, since sometimes he could make a nice spy. However, he can think of it later, while there are issues right now.</p>
<p>And he feels JM clutching his sleeve like it can help him stay quiet. It even makes Moran want to like hug his shoulders a bit, telling to relax. For sure he does nothing.</p>
<p>Finally, those guys are completely gone, and Moran opens one door a bit more to let faint light get into the container, and turns to face JM.</p>
<p>"A blowjob here, really? Are you a teen?" he smirks, yet it looks more like a nonchalant soft smile now. Then he takes a look at his wristwatch and adds, "You’ve got like less than half of hour if you want to get to the opening ceremony in time, considering where we are and how could we get there without popping out of nowhere."</p>
<p>He doesn’t ask for an explanation of why he shouldn’t see stuff now, first—because he can understand a bit later, second—because no questions make JM much more talkative. Freaky genius is used to tons of questions people ask him, so once he receives patient silence, he can’t wait for long and sometimes can spill something interesting. Especially with Moran, since Colonel has never ever used absolutely anything against JM, even when he really could. A trust or a reason, or a blackmail effect, whatever.</p>
<p>"Whatever you wanted to do here, better do it quick. We can’t be sure when the next idiot would go for a walk around here."</p>
<p>This time, Moran stays at the exit, since he saw whatever he could already. He won’t be able to see more IDs or papers, and old phones and guns are no interest for him. So, the only one option is being kinda on duty.</p>
<p>And—watch every JM’s move while listening to the surroundings. What he does, where he steps, what he takes and what he leaves. The changes in his face even, when it’s possible; and maybe it’s the time to feel like a predator again—but Moran would compare that process with looking at the perfect work of art in some famous museum. Almost fascinating in a weird way.</p>`
};

pagesData[76] = {
    author: "JM", // or "SM" depending on parity (even index = JM, odd = SM)
    text: `<p>"Promise you'll let me do it when it's over, pleeease," JM teases, feeling relieved partly because the "happy wanderers" left, and partly because Moran has no visible intention of bringing up the issue with those ID's; however, though it's temporarily dismissed, JM gotta think of something to lie about until the moment it'll pop up again.</p>
<p>It's been a while since they were on a job together, and it's inspiring to see Moran just smirk at his goofy commentary, like the closeness of a critical situation made him feel good and natural about himself. Well, he and JM wouldn't become partners in crime if they didn't get high on this, each in his own way.</p>
<p>Now back to business. JM folds one of the blanks and puts it into his inner pocket. "Nah it's done here. Let's get out. It's party time."</p>
<p>He picks up the wire cutters and jumps off the truck after Moran, allowing him to lend a hand. They actually need to be in the celebration hall about 15 min early, and that's where Sebastian's regalia are going to come into action, because JM needs to talk in private to the Lord Mayor himself; and usually it's a tricky thing to do since he's constantly surrounded by a hive of either his guards or the crowd. And before that – they'll have to pass the security check under their phony names.</p>
<p>JM steps closer to the edge of the pier; down there, the dark water is splashing, rocking the clumps of sludge and mud; and there's the specific smell. He throws the wire cutters in the water and lets them drown.</p>
<p>Still something feels unfinished. While Moran keeps patroling the area, he ponders a little, making a circle around the truck and then decides to inspect its cabin. There's a can of gasoline on the seat, half-empty; JM drags it outside, almost tripping.</p>
<p>"Do you have a lighter?"</p>
<p>Maybe this measure would be excessive since this place is gonna blow anyway, but with this container specifically, the one marked "Blacktorne", it's better to make sure and leave nothing but ashes inside.</p>`
};

pagesData[77] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>It seems quite easy to simply ignore all the usual shit JM’s babbling, same easy it is to get out first and turn back to lend a hand. All the time Moran keeps himself highly alert in case someone else would walk around here, and still watches JM throwing the wire cutters into the muddy water.</p>
<p>He waits patiently while JM looks a bit doubtful, then while he peeks into the truck. Then he asks for a lighter. Here we go, Moran thinks, taking a standard Zippo out of his pocket. Plain metal and fire, nothing else; something expensive enough but still nothing to feel sorry about.</p>
<p>"Have fun," he says, tossing the lighter to JM. "You actually got a funny way of flirting."
In the end, it will all get on fire anyway. So, right now some fire won’t be a real issue, yet they would have even less time to quickly get away.</p>
<p>Just like in bloody good old times.</p>
<p>They manage to get away in time. They manage to make it neatly enough so to appear in a proper place and proper time. They manage to easily pass the nervous safety check using fake documents. Moran immediately changes, putting on his usual mask of cold but polite social demeanor, being just an excellent example of a noble British officer he is.</p>
Years ago, they’ve already played that game. Usually JM was the leader all the time, but he was also a perfect actor so sometimes he switched to a companion role, making himself a perfect noone: people tend to ignore persons like that. Adjuncts, secretaries, assistants, such people were more like furniture or gadgets. Well, their problems.</p>
<p>So they’ve used it successfully. When needed, Moran would catch the attention, while JM would blend into his shadow, keeping an eye on everything he needs; some doors that won’t open just for anyone could be easily unlocked like that. A good team play, one can say.</p>
<p>The same they were doing right now. Getting right to the Lord Mayor is hell of a challenge at a party like that. And they don’t have much time.</p>
<p>"Are we still hitting the deadlines?" Moran asks in a whisper, and upon receiving a confirmation, makes a final push towards the man JM needs. A lot of security, a lot of mass-media, but sometimes such a bustle could serve well. And goddammit, Sebastian feels such a nice thrill right now like he’s playing a tricky card game. Would it all really burn down tonight? Probably yes. Would Moran feel sorry for that? Hell no.</p>`
};

pagesData[78] = {
    author: "JM",
    text: `<p>Once all the old stuff gets soaked in gasoline, JM sends a fire to crawl inside along the oily trail and quickly illuminate every corner of this rusty box. Paper burns first; plastic melts, releasing toxic smoke into the air. JM shuts the door, abandoning those memories forever.</p>
<p>The endless walking is tiring but luckily they get there to the minute and blend with the crowd of elegantly dressed people waiting in a line to pass the security check. JM can't see anyone else wearing pink so far. Shit... The Zippo makes the metal detector beep, but what's so suspicious about a lighter?</p>
<p>The celebration hall is made almost completely out of glass by today's fashion; every building that falls under reconstruction ends up obtaining a glass facade, usually deformed in some unorthodox style. Guests are required to go to the roof straight away: on the terrace, there are tables served with catering and champagne, and a perfect view of the sky darkening slowly above the port zone and the driveway; seagulls floating in circles between the cranes.</p>
<p>The Lord Mayor has not arrived yet, probably stuck in a traffic, so everyone's just munching on canapés and trying to chat, while the technician is setting up the mic. However, a significant number of reporters is already there, filming the stage, the wide staircase and all the best-looking spots. Sebastian was right about the delays that are usually made during this kind of events, so the best thing he and JM can do is play it natural; try not to look too out-of-place; which is rather easy yet because Moran makes a flawlessly collected impression, and JM makes an impression of a man who could fancy the canapés, since all this walking around the terminal has already made him starve.</p>
<p>Having fetched some bruschettas with surprisingly good salmon, JM returns to see Moran in company of some lad in the rank of a captian and his fiancé, trying to start a conversation. What's your military unit, wait, let me guess. The former officer killed himself, what a tragedy, did you know him well? All this nonsense, JM thinks, while playing a staring game with the girl, wondering if she'll realise they're not welcome. It's not like he feels possessive about Sebastian, or maybe it is and he does; but still it's somewhat satisfying to see Moran receive appreciation in a place like this. The girl is wearing a silky gown and large diamond earrings. JM gives her a smug smile, as if saying: "My man is cooler than yours :)"</p>
<p>Soon after they leave, another voice breaks the peace, now addressing JM.</p>
<p>"Good God... Where did you get that?"</p>
<p>"What?"</p>
<p>"I know Alexander McQueen when I see one. Is it a limited collection? You had it tailored, didn't you?"</p>
<p>"Ah. Yeah."</p>
<p>"The lapels, the collar... There really are three of them in the whole world, five at best, I think. Years ago I was dying to get this specific suit, but somebody snatched the last one right from under my nose. Can you believe it?"</p>
<p>"Unbelievable..."</p>
<p>Meanwhile an odd fuss began, and the crowd started to buzz as they saw a row of black cars park on the driveway. The Lord Mayor is followed by a strange bustling atmosphere and a disgusting amount of more reporters. JM tries to dismiss the conversation with the fashion enthusiast without saying a blunt "Fuck off", but fails, because the man keeps following them upon their attempts to physically leave this interaction.</p>
<p>"No, I'm serious, where did you get it?"</p>
<p>"I really don't remember. Now excuse us..."</p>
<p>"Do you still have the number of your dealer?"</p>
<p>"No, I don't think so. Mr. Stephen... Or whatever your name is..." JM mutters, unable to concentrate because he's trying to keep an eye on the hive of people, with the Lord Mayor in its center, passing the reporters and now moving up the stairs. Finally, he turns to Sebastian and begs: "Get rid of him, for God's sake!"</p>
<p>* * *</p>
<p>A series of handshakes, a bow for the cameras; a glass of champagne splashed on Lord Mayor's jacket, and he goes to a separate room for a quick change. Leaving Sebastian to distract attention, JM sneaks inside.</p>
<p>The Lord Mayor is a man in his forties. He looks suspiciously at the intruder and prepares to call for the security.</p>
<p>"A glorious event, isn't it? The grand opening..." JM starts politely.</p>
<p>"Are you a reporter? I already spoke to your colleagues. You're not supposed to be here. I'm giving a speech in two minutes, so you better get out, or my guards will make you."</p>
<p>"No need to get so protective, sir. I'm not a reporter. I represent the Blackthorne Holdings company; an old friend of yours sent me to say hello. And by the way, you know too well about things one is not supposed to do, especially while running for mayor."</p>
<p>The man stops himself mid-adjusting his tie.</p>
<p>"What does this mean?"</p>
<p>"Oh, this could mean nothing. Or... I don't know! In this case, I'm not the one to decide."</p>
<p>He steps closer, pulling out the blank he had fetched and speaks to the Lord Mayor in a whisper. JM doesn't really need anything aside from his words to make the man do what he wants him to do, but it's an extra way of saying "I got you". Again, this whole conversation might be an excessive measure, since it's easy enough to just swap the buttons and make him press the bad one by deception, then observe the total shock on his face.</p>
<p>But JM wants him to know what he's doing, and still. fucking. do it. To be completely conscious of the consequences and still press the button, because he has no other choice; or because the alternative to blowing up a multimillion-dollar project might be so much worse.</p>
<p>* * *</p>
<p>Five minutes pass, and the Lord Mayor appears on the roof, looking a little bit disturbed, but you can't really tell from a distance. He's invited on the stage and starts giving his speech, expressing gratitude for the sponsors.</p>
<p>JM joins Sebastian in the crowd of listeners, looking like nothing happened; as if he spent those five minutes in a bathroom and not whispering evil things in someone's ear.</p>
<p>Soon enough, a huge golden button is presented on a platter and served in front of the Mayor. He puts the mic aside and hesitates, looking at the button for ten, twenty seconds... a confusingly long time already... probably considering if he should believe what the Man in Pink told him. It might be a bluff, after all…</p>`
};

pagesData[79] = {
    author: "SM", // or "SM" depending on parity (even index = JM, odd = SM)
    text: `<p>It’s so bloody easy to play a part of beau monde since Moran actually was a part of it, being a heir to a noble old diplomat dynasty, and no war experience could erase that skill of fake socialization taken in with mother’s milk. Not that he really likes it, for sure.
Yet they have to wait for the fucking Lord Mayor, and the best way to look natural is play natural, which means small talks, polite smiles, and a glass of something in the hand. The moment Moran finds a nice place to wait for JM who’s gone hunting some treats, he hears a voice nearby.</p>
<p>"Colonel," a guy with captain’s stars says, saluting him while his girlfriend smiles politely and makes an awkward attempt of some curtsy. Moran doesn’t even raise a brow, answering with a cold "Captain" and even more cold smile. Seems like that guy isn’t comfortable here, no wonder he was drawn to an officer of same corps. He starts a conversation even more awkward that his girl’s behaviour; but well, Moran talks to him calmly, showing zero emotions when the guy mentions a tragical suicide of another one officer.</p>
<p>Well, Moran did what he did. He was even kind enough to mention Thompson still has a chance. And if someone doesn’t want to grab the little chances, well… Moran is not sorry.</p>
<p>He feels JM coming back, and he sees the girl staring at him. Let her think whatever. Let her even gossip with her boyfriend trying to find out who’s that fancy-dressed guy at his side. It’s even funny. Would they think it’s an assistant? Or a lover? Or just another one bored guest here just keeping to someone he knows?</p>
<p>As soon as they leave, Moran actually would like to have a word with JM, but he’s late for just a couple of seconds since that stupid pink suit finally draws attention. Moran even feels some malicious joy watching Moriarty trying not to start a conversation. The fashion-lover with eyes fixed on jacket lapels but not the other man’s face just keeps babbling.
It’s a real fun, if you ask.</p>
<p>Moran does completely nothing about it. He just enjoys the moment, even when the bloody Lord Mayor finally arrives and they try to reach the place with that talkative dude on their tails, because seeing JM getting so annoyed is kind of cheerful. Yet when JM asks in a low voice to get rid of the follower, Sebastian just does it in a very quick and simple way. One step back, one turn to catch the other man’s eyes in a cold sight, and one dangerously cold, calm phrase: "Would you please mind leaving us alone, sir?"</p>
<p>This politeness is filled with a menace, especially when the poor McQueen fan feels a strong arm not letting him make a step forward. It doesn’t last long, since the danger is obvoius. Muttering something under his breath, the guy disappears.</p>
<p>Moran knows he can draw attention by acting like that, but well, today he does really have to draw some attention. He plays like a perfect red herring, letting JM execute his plan. It’s a good old feel of thrill, of a perfect teamplay—or rather, a double since they make a more than perfect duo for anything. They make it all seamlessly, performing an ideal accident for Lord Mayor to get away for a couple of minutes. And for one hell of a talk.</p>
<p>JM skillfully disappears right after, while Moran grabs some attention to keep it and let that disappearance be invisible. All he has to do now is just continue the play and then, when needed, quickly move aside.</p>
<p>Same time he observes the location, looking for a best place to watch the drama. So when JM returns, Moran casually leads him aside as if they really want to hear the Lord Mayor’s speech. He chooses a spot near the crowd, not standing off but blending into the surroundings. There’s a nice view both of the stage and of the Port itself; and also there’s an emergency exit in couple of steps, since if everything goes fine, there’ll be panic so it’s nice to have a quick way out.</p>
<p>"Nice," Moran smirks slightly while listening to usual ‘that was a lot of hard and important work done’ bullshit. All those speeches are the same. He glances at JM, as if trying to read his face, then checks the people around them. All clear.</p>
<p>And then there’s a big fat pause Lord Mayor takes looking at the freaking stupid button. He waits and waits, and suddenly there’s a playful loud voice out of the crowd, "Oh, just push it already!" Somebody nearby cries an agreeful "C’mon", and then people begin to applaud enthusiatically, maybe thinking that this pause is meant to make the moment more solemn.</p>
<p>And then, the Lord Mayor, pale as a ghost, pushed the fucking golden button.</p>
<p>First few seconds, nothing happens. Moran can even see a shadow of relief on politician’s face (well, knowing JM it wasn’t diffucult to guess why he had to talk to the Lord Mayor). And then, there’s a distant yet very loud sound which calls to some deep sick memories of flashpoint experience, making Moran stiffen hard against his will. A good old ‘boom’, complete with a dark smoke, followed by another and another one, a speechless crowd, a pale face of the Lord Mayor.</p>
<p>Moran turns to the Port like everyone, and watches for few very long second.</p>
<p>"It’s fucking beautiful," he says very quietly so only JM would head, and these words are absolutely genuine. And the look on Moran’s face might be still composed and neutral, yet his eyes betray him showing a pure excitement in that evil moment.</p>`
};

pagesData[80] = {
    author: "JM", // or "SM" depending on parity (even index = JM, odd = SM)
    text: `<p>One must wonder what's running through the Mayor's mind during these moments of endless hesitation, while he's preparing to execute what seems to be the hardest decision in his life. Perhaps, he's telling himself to think clearly, assess different outcomes, visualize his further actions in case the threat is real. Seek legal help, deny your knowledge, act as a victim of the circumstances.</p>
<p>JM knows a decision can weight heavy, but there're at least three loopholes:</p>
<p>1) being pressured by a violent authority, which will make it easier to waive responsibility;</p>
<p>2) having no confidence in whether it's not a bluff, which will make hope more desperate*;</p>
<p>3) the shortage of time and an impatient audience, which will make the decision more rushed.</p>
<p>*JM himself has said to the Mayor: "It might, or might not go 'kaboom!' The real question is: whether you believe in your own luck. Do you?"</p>
<p>All of these three factors guide the man's hand when he finally presses that button. The spotlights seem to start moving, like in a circus, at some point almost aligning into the letter M in the dark sky; if they did so, JM would consider this an amusing coincidence, but the laser beams fly apart and just freeze in more solemn anticipation.</p>
<p>At first – yes, there's noting but the inaudible sigh of relief coming from Mayor; a distant blast, unimpressive at first, like a punchline to an obscene joke, and some of the guests laugh: it's a minor technical problem, or some crane flipped over, maybe.</p>
<p>Then the first real blow makes the glass walls tremble, like a shell that exploded nearby and sent a shockwave for miles around. The fountains of fire rise tall one after another in various spots of the landscape, and thick smoke starts spreading above it like a thundercloud.</p>
<p>JM sneaks beside Moran, embracing him by the shoulder, and feels his muscles and posture stiffen.</p>
<p>"You like the fireworks?" he whispers in reply. "What a wicked little Colonel..!"</p>
<p>A minute passes until it's finally remembered to start the alarm. While being quickly escorted to his car, the Lord Mayor still tries to find the Pink Man among the crowd, but it's impossible now. JM and Sebastian have to retreat to their Porsche, parked at the far entrance, then JM tells Moran to drive along the riverbank as far as possible. The horizon glows orange, meaning the port is already fully ignited, and the fire trucks race that direction with loud hooting, whereas the Porsche drives to the other.</p>
<p>Finally JM asks Moran to pull over to the side of the road and park on the grass, between thickets of reeds. From where they are, the fire is still slightly visible, but the hooting concedes to the sounds of the river fauna. Aside from frogs, perhaps, there's no one around, and JM enjoys that moment of no more crowds with zero spatial intelligence. They sit in silence for some time.</p>
<p>Then he says that they'll likely need to abandon the car in an environmentally unfriendly way (which is: to make it sink into the river), have a walk to the nearest gas station and find themselves a cab. But first they need to rest a little bit, and also...</p>
<p>"Do you remember what you promised?" he asks, spreading himself wearily across the seat, with his head down in Sebastian's lap, ignoring the fact that he actually promised nothing.</p>`
};

pagesData[81] = {
    author: "SM",
    text: `<p>Looking at the ‘fireworks’ with pure admiration, Moran doesn’t deny it’s kinda sick. But whatever. He doesn’t care of those who are just losing hell of a money right now, neither he cares of Lord Mayor and the responsible persons. That is a freaky fun, truly. So when he feels Moriarty’s arm on his shoulders, he even manages to lose some tension in his muscles a little bit.</p>
<p>He’d like to watch more and enjoy the panic, but they have to get away before it spreads, so they quickly and neatly disappear in emergency exit, leaving the chaos behind.</p>
<p>Since everyone around is genuinely shocked, it’s quite easy to pass through the building and the parking lot, reaching the Porsche, and simply drive away. It’s actually a common thing with big crimes: the one who’s in charge just simply walks away while everyone just selflessly goes into panic mode.</p>
<p>And they drive away with a normal speed, no rush, no fuss, keeping bloody calm. Moran even finds himself slightly drumming his fingers on the steering wheel in time to the ‘London Bridge Is Falling Down’ playing in his head.</p>
<p>Finally, JM asks to stop, and he does, driving poor Porsche right into the grass. Sebastian cuts the engine and turns the lights off, and then there’s a nice and even cozy silence. Dark car won’t be seen from the road, and there’s nothing except frogs and insects around, so there’s no inner alarm right now. Moran lets himself relax a little bit, shifting his seat back and reclining it a little.</p>
<p>They both are silent. Moran thinks about the Port, and how many people were involved in that plan, while he just skimmed the cream; then JM says they would have to get rid of that car and find a cab. Moran can’t help himself but laugh quietly thinking how stupid they would look while searching for a cab at some gas station here in some boonies. Though well, whatever.</p>
<p>Then Moriarty changes his position, taking a bit bizarre one, and asks a question in a tone which sounds more like a claim.</p>
<p>"Why, I do," Moran says nonchalantly. "I promised a good old nothing."</p>
<p>He knows such trap-questions very well, and also he likes to tease JM a little bit by acting like he doesn’t understand what’s behind. And maybe it’s playing with fire at some point, but goddammit—he does really like to play with fire.</p>
<p>Also there’s a shadow of a very weird subconscious wish as he feels that bright head on his lap, since Sebastian has to make a little effort so not to run his fingers through JM’s hair in an almost gentle way.</p>`
};

pagesData[82] = {
